   <h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Netherlands</h1>

     From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia

     <div class="mw-parser-output">
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       This article is about the constituent country. For the sovereign state, see <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_the_Netherlands" title="Kingdom of the Netherlands">Kingdom of the Netherlands</a>. For all other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_(disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig" title="Netherlands (disambiguation)">Netherlands (disambiguation)</a>.
      </div>

         <td>
          <div class="plainlist">
           <ul>
            <li style="white-space:nowrap;">50.1% <a href="/wiki/Irreligion" title="Irreligion">No religion</a></li>
            <li style="white-space:nowrap;">43.8% <a href="/wiki/Christianity" title="Christianity">Christianity</a></li>
            <li style="white-space:nowrap;">—23.7% <a href="/wiki/Catholic_Church_in_the_Netherlands" title="Catholic Church in the Netherlands">Catholicism</a></li>
            <li style="white-space:nowrap;">—18.1% <a href="/wiki/Protestantism" title="Protestantism">Protestantism</a></li>
            <li style="white-space:nowrap;">—2.0% Other <a href="/wiki/List_of_Christian_denominations" title="List of Christian denominations">Christian</a></li>
            <li style="white-space:nowrap;">4.9% <a href="/wiki/Islam_in_the_Netherlands" title="Islam in the Netherlands">Islam</a></li>
            <li style="white-space:nowrap;">1.2% <a href="/wiki/Religion_in_the_Netherlands" title="Religion in the Netherlands">Others</a></li>

      <p>The <b>Netherlands</b> (<a href="/wiki/Dutch_language" title="Dutch language">Dutch</a>: <i lang="nl">Nederland</i> <small></small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA/Dutch" title="Help:IPA/Dutch">[ˈneːdərlɑnt]</a></span> <span class="nowrap" style="font-size:85%">(<span class="unicode haudio"><span class="fn"><span style="white-space:nowrap;margin-right:.25em;"><a href="/wiki/File:Nl-Nederland.ogg" title="About this sound"><img alt="About this sound" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png" decoding="async" width="11" height="11" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/17px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/22px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="20" data-file-height="20"></a></span><a href="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0a/Nl-Nederland.ogg" class="internal" title="Nl-Nederland.ogg">listen</a></span></span>)</span>), informally <b><a href="/wiki/Holland" title="Holland">Holland</a></b>,<sup id="cite_ref-Netherlands_vs._Holland_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Netherlands_vs._Holland-20">[13]</a></sup> is a country primarily located in <a href="/wiki/Western_Europe" title="Western Europe">Western Europe</a> and partly in the <a href="/wiki/Caribbean" title="Caribbean">Caribbean</a>. It is the largest of four constituent countries of the <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_the_Netherlands" title="Kingdom of the Netherlands">Kingdom of the Netherlands</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[14]</a></sup> In <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a>, The Netherlands consists of <a href="/wiki/Provinces_of_the_Netherlands" title="Provinces of the Netherlands">12 provinces</a>, bordering <a href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">Germany</a> to the east, <a href="/wiki/Belgium" title="Belgium">Belgium</a> to the south, and the <a href="/wiki/North_Sea" title="North Sea">North Sea</a> to the northwest, with <a href="/wiki/Maritime_boundary" title="Maritime boundary">maritime borders</a> in the North Sea with those countries and the <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[15]</a></sup> In the Caribbean, it consists of three <a href="/wiki/Caribbean_Netherlands" title="Caribbean Netherlands">special municipalities</a>: the islands of <a href="/wiki/Bonaire" title="Bonaire">Bonaire</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sint_Eustatius" title="Sint Eustatius">Sint Eustatius</a> and <a href="/wiki/Saba" title="Saba">Saba</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[h]</a></sup> The country's official language is <a href="/wiki/Dutch_language" title="Dutch language">Dutch</a>, with <a href="/wiki/West_Frisian_language" title="West Frisian language">West Frisian</a> as a secondary official language in the province of <a href="/wiki/Friesland" title="Friesland">Friesland</a>, and <a href="/wiki/English_language" title="English language">English</a> and <a href="/wiki/Papiamentu" class="mw-redirect" title="Papiamentu">Papiamentu</a> as secondary official languages in the Caribbean Netherlands.<sup id="cite_ref-official-and-recognised-languages_2-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-official-and-recognised-languages-2">[1]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Low_Saxon" title="Dutch Low Saxon">Dutch Low Saxon</a> and <a href="/wiki/Limburgish" title="Limburgish">Limburgish</a> are recognised regional languages (spoken in the east and southeast respectively), while <a href="/wiki/Sinte_Romani" title="Sinte Romani">Sinte Romani</a> and <a href="/wiki/Yiddish" title="Yiddish">Yiddish</a> are recognised non-territorial languages.<sup id="cite_ref-official-and-recognised-languages_2-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-official-and-recognised-languages-2">[1]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The four largest cities in the Netherlands are <a href="/wiki/Amsterdam" title="Amsterdam">Amsterdam</a>, <a href="/wiki/Rotterdam" title="Rotterdam">Rotterdam</a>, <a href="/wiki/The_Hague" title="The Hague">The Hague</a> and <a href="/wiki/Utrecht" title="Utrecht">Utrecht</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[17]</a></sup> Amsterdam is the country's most populous city and nominal <a href="/wiki/Capital_of_the_Netherlands" title="Capital of the Netherlands">capital</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[18]</a></sup> while The Hague holds the seat of the <a href="/wiki/States_General_of_the_Netherlands" title="States General of the Netherlands">States General</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cabinet_of_the_Netherlands" title="Cabinet of the Netherlands">Cabinet</a> and <a href="/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_Netherlands" title="Supreme Court of the Netherlands">Supreme Court</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[19]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Port_of_Rotterdam" title="Port of Rotterdam">Port of Rotterdam</a> is the busiest <a href="/wiki/Port" title="Port">seaport</a> in Europe, and the busiest in any country outside <a href="/wiki/East_Asia" title="East Asia">East Asia</a> and <a href="/wiki/Southeast_Asia" title="Southeast Asia">Southeast Asia</a>, behind only <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a> and <a href="/wiki/Singapore" title="Singapore">Singapore</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[20]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Amsterdam_Airport_Schiphol" title="Amsterdam Airport Schiphol">Amsterdam Airport Schiphol</a> is the busiest airport in the Netherlands, and the third busiest in Europe. The country is a founding member of the <a href="/wiki/European_Union" title="European Union">EU</a>, <a href="/wiki/Eurozone" title="Eurozone">Eurozone</a>, <a href="/wiki/Group_of_Ten_(economics)" title="Group of Ten (economics)">G10</a>, <a href="/wiki/NATO" title="NATO">NATO</a>, <a href="/wiki/Organisation_for_Economic_Co-operation_and_Development" class="mw-redirect" title="Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development">OECD</a> and <a href="/wiki/World_Trade_Organization" title="World Trade Organization">WTO</a>, as well as a part of the <a href="/wiki/Schengen_Area" title="Schengen Area">Schengen Area</a> and the trilateral <a href="/wiki/Benelux" title="Benelux">Benelux Union</a>. It hosts several <a href="/wiki/Intergovernmental_organization" title="Intergovernmental organization">intergovernmental organisations</a> and <a href="/wiki/International_court" title="International court">international courts</a>, many of which are centered in The Hague, which is consequently dubbed 'the world's legal capital'.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">[21]</a></sup> </p>
      <p><span class="anchor" id="name"></span><i>Netherlands</i> literally means "lower countries" in reference to its low elevation and flat topography, with only about 50% of its land exceeding 1 metre (3&nbsp;ft 3&nbsp;in) <a href="/wiki/Above_mean_sea_level" class="mw-redirect" title="Above mean sea level">above sea level</a>, and nearly 26% falling below sea level.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-30">[22]</a></sup> Most of the areas below sea level, known as <a href="/wiki/Polder" title="Polder"><i>polders</i></a>, are the result of <a href="/wiki/Land_reclamation_in_the_Netherlands" title="Land reclamation in the Netherlands">land reclamation that began in the 14th century</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Cavendish_2003_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Cavendish_2003-31">[23]</a></sup> Colloquially or informally the Netherlands are occasionally referred to by the <a href="/wiki/Pars_pro_toto" title="Pars pro toto">pars pro toto</a> <i>Holland</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-Netherlands_vs._Holland_20-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Netherlands_vs._Holland-20">[13]</a></sup> With a population of 17.4 million people, all living within a total area of roughly 41,800 square kilometres (16,100&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi)—of which the land area is 33,500 square kilometres (12,900&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi)—the Netherlands is the <a href="/wiki/List_of_sovereign_states_and_dependent_territories_by_population_density" class="mw-redirect" title="List of sovereign states and dependent territories by population density">12th most densely populated</a> country in the world and the <a href="/wiki/Area_and_population_of_European_countries" title="Area and population of European countries">2nd most densely populated</a> country in the European Union, with a density of 521 per square kilometre (1,350/sq&nbsp;mi). Nevertheless, it is the world's second-largest <a href="/wiki/Export" title="Export">exporter</a> of food and agricultural products, owing to its <a href="/wiki/Fertile_soil" class="mw-redirect" title="Fertile soil">fertile soil</a>, mild climate, <a href="/wiki/Intensive_farming" title="Intensive farming">intensive agriculture</a> and <a href="/wiki/List_of_Dutch_inventions_and_innovations" title="List of Dutch inventions and innovations">inventiveness</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[24]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-hollandtrade.com_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hollandtrade.com-33">[25]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nationalgeographic.com_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nationalgeographic.com-34">[26]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The Netherlands has been a <a href="/wiki/Parliamentary_system" title="Parliamentary system">parliamentary</a> <a href="/wiki/Constitutional_monarchy" title="Constitutional monarchy">constitutional monarchy</a> with a <a href="/wiki/Unitary_state" title="Unitary state">unitary structure</a> since 1848. The country has a tradition of <a href="/wiki/Pillarisation" title="Pillarisation">pillarisation</a> and a long record of <a href="/wiki/Social_tolerance" class="mw-redirect" title="Social tolerance">social tolerance</a>, having legalised <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_the_Netherlands" title="Abortion in the Netherlands">abortion</a>, <a href="/wiki/Prostitution_in_the_Netherlands" title="Prostitution in the Netherlands">prostitution</a> and <a href="/wiki/Euthanasia_in_the_Netherlands" title="Euthanasia in the Netherlands">human euthanasia</a>, along with maintaining a liberal <a href="/wiki/Drug_policy_of_the_Netherlands" title="Drug policy of the Netherlands">drug policy</a>. The Netherlands abolished the <a href="/wiki/Capital_punishment_in_the_Netherlands" title="Capital punishment in the Netherlands">death penalty</a> in Civil Law in 1870, though it was not completely removed until a new constitution was approved in 1983. The Netherlands allowed <a href="/wiki/Women%27s_suffrage" title="Women's suffrage">women's suffrage</a> in 1919, before becoming the world's first country to legalise <a href="/wiki/Same-sex_marriage_in_the_Netherlands" title="Same-sex marriage in the Netherlands">same-sex marriage</a> in 2001. Its <a href="/wiki/Mixed_market" class="mw-redirect" title="Mixed market">mixed-market</a> <a href="/wiki/Developed_country" title="Developed country">advanced economy</a> had the <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(PPP)_per_capita" title="List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita">eleventh-highest</a> <a href="/wiki/Per_capita_income" title="Per capita income">per capita income</a> globally.<sup id="cite_ref-GDP_IMF_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GDP_IMF-35">[27]</a></sup> The Netherlands ranks among the highest in international indexes of <a href="/wiki/Press_freedom" class="mw-redirect" title="Press freedom">press freedom</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">[28]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Economic_freedom" title="Economic freedom">economic freedom</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">[29]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Human_Development_Index" title="Human Development Index">human development</a> and <a href="/wiki/Quality_of_life" title="Quality of life">quality of life</a>, as well as <a href="/wiki/Happiness" title="Happiness">happiness</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[30]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">[i]</a></sup> In 2019, it ranked tenth on the human development index and fifth on the 2019 <a href="/wiki/World_Happiness_Report" title="World Happiness Report">World Happiness Index</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">[32]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">[33]</a></sup> </p> 
      <div id="toc" class="toc" role="navigation" aria-labelledby="mw-toc-heading">

      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Etymology">Etymology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Etymology">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/Terminology_of_the_Low_Countries" title="Terminology of the Low Countries">Terminology of the Low Countries</a>
      </div> 
      <p>The Netherlands' turbulent history and shifts of power resulted in exceptionally many and widely varying names in different languages. There is diversity even within languages. In English, the Netherlands is also called <a href="/wiki/Holland" title="Holland">Holland</a> or (part of) <a href="/wiki/The_Low_Countries" class="mw-redirect" title="The Low Countries">the Low Countries</a>, whereas the term <i>"<a href="/wiki/Dutch_language" title="Dutch language">Dutch</a>"</i> is used as the <a href="/wiki/Demonym" title="Demonym">demonym</a> and adjectival form. </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="The_Netherlands_and_the_Low_Countries">The Netherlands and the Low Countries</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: The Netherlands and the Low Countries">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <p>The region called the <a href="/wiki/Low_Countries" title="Low Countries">Low Countries</a> (comprising <a href="/wiki/Belgium" title="Belgium">Belgium</a>, the Netherlands and <a href="/wiki/Luxembourg" title="Luxembourg">Luxembourg</a>) and the Country of the Netherlands, have the same <a href="/wiki/Toponymy" title="Toponymy">toponymy</a>. Place names with <i>Neder</i>, <i>Nieder</i>, <i>Nedre</i>, <i>Nether</i>, <i>Lage(r)</i> or <i>Low(er)</i> (in <a href="/wiki/Germanic_languages" title="Germanic languages">Germanic languages</a>) and <i>Bas</i> or <i>Inferior</i> (in <a href="/wiki/Romance_languages" title="Romance languages">Romance languages</a>) are in use in low-lying places all over Europe. They are sometimes used in a <a href="/wiki/Deictic" class="mw-redirect" title="Deictic">deictic</a> relation to a higher ground that consecutively is indicated as <i>Super(ior)</i>, <i>Up(per)</i>, <i>Op(per)</i>, <i>Ober</i>, <i>Boven</i>, <i>High</i>, <i>Haut</i> or <i>Hoch</i>. In the case of the Low Countries / Netherlands the geographical location of the <i>lower</i> region has been more or less downstream and near the sea. The geographical location of the upper region, however, changed tremendously over time, depending on the location of the economic and military power governing the Low Countries area. The <a href="/wiki/Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">Romans</a> made a distinction between the Roman provinces of downstream <a href="/wiki/Germania_Inferior" title="Germania Inferior">Germania Inferior</a> (nowadays part of Belgium and the Netherlands) and upstream <a href="/wiki/Germania_Superior" title="Germania Superior">Germania Superior</a> (nowadays part of Germany). The designation 'Low' to refer to the region returns again in the 10th century Duchy of <a href="/wiki/Lower_Lorraine" class="mw-redirect" title="Lower Lorraine">Lower Lorraine</a>, that covered much of the Low Countries.<sup id="cite_ref-Franks_(Columbia_Encyclopedia)_43-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Franks_(Columbia_Encyclopedia)-43">[34]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[35]</a></sup> But this time the corresponding <i>Upper</i> region is <a href="/wiki/Upper_Lorraine" class="mw-redirect" title="Upper Lorraine">Upper Lorraine</a>, in nowadays Northern France. </p>
      <p>The <a href="/wiki/Dukes_of_Burgundy" class="mw-redirect" title="Dukes of Burgundy">Dukes of Burgundy</a>, who ruled from their residence in the Low Countries in the 15th century, used the term <i>les pays de par deçà</i> ("the lands over here") for the Low Countries, as opposed to <i>les pays de par delà</i> ("the lands over there") for their original homeland: <a href="/wiki/Burgundy" title="Burgundy">Burgundy</a> in present-day east-central France.<sup id="cite_ref-BlockmansPrevenier2010_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BlockmansPrevenier2010-45">[36]</a></sup> Under <a href="/wiki/Habsburg_Netherlands" title="Habsburg Netherlands">Habsburg rule</a>, <i>Les pays de par deçà</i> developed in <i>pays d'embas</i> ("lands down-here"),<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">[37]</a></sup> a deictic expression in relation to other Habsburg possessions like Hungary and Austria. This was translated as <i>Neder-landen</i> in contemporary Dutch official documents.<sup id="cite_ref-Lem_47-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lem-47">[38]</a></sup> From a regional point of view, <i>Niderlant</i> was also the area between the <a href="/wiki/Meuse_(river)" class="mw-redirect" title="Meuse (river)">Meuse</a> and the lower <a href="/wiki/Rhine" title="Rhine">Rhine</a> in the late Middle Ages. The area known as <i>Oberland</i> (High country) was in this deictic context considered to begin approximately at the nearby higher located <a href="/wiki/Cologne" title="Cologne">Cologne</a>. </p>
      <p>From the mid-sixteenth century on, the "Low Countries" and the "Netherlands" lost their original deictic meaning. They were probably the most commonly used names, besides <a href="/wiki/Flanders" title="Flanders">Flanders</a>, a <i><a href="/wiki/Pars_pro_toto" title="Pars pro toto">pars pro toto</a></i> for the Low Countries, especially in Romance language speaking Europe. The <a href="/wiki/Eighty_Years%27_War" title="Eighty Years' War">Eighty Years' War</a> (1568–1648) divided the Low Countries into an independent northern <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Republic" title="Dutch Republic">Dutch Republic</a> (or <a href="/wiki/Latinisation_of_names" title="Latinisation of names">Latinised</a> <i>Belgica Foederata</i>, "Federated Netherlands", the precursor state of the Netherlands) and a Spanish controlled <a href="/wiki/Southern_Netherlands" title="Southern Netherlands">Southern Netherlands</a> (Latinised <i>Belgica Regia</i>, "Royal Netherlands", the precursor state of Belgium). The Low Countries today is a designation that includes the countries of the Netherlands, Belgium and Luxembourg, although in most <a href="/wiki/Romance_languages" title="Romance languages">Romance languages</a>, the term "Low Countries" is used as the name for the Netherlands specifically. It is used synonymous with the more neutral and geopolitical term <a href="/wiki/Benelux" title="Benelux">Benelux</a>. </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Holland">Holland</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Holland">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <p>The Netherlands is also referred to as <a href="/wiki/Holland" title="Holland">Holland</a> in various languages, including English. The region of Holland proper consists of <a href="/wiki/North_Holland" title="North Holland">North</a> and <a href="/wiki/South_Holland" title="South Holland">South Holland</a>, two of the nation's twelve provinces, formerly a single province, and earlier still, the <a href="/wiki/County_of_Holland" title="County of Holland">County of Holland</a>, a remnant of the dissolved <a href="/wiki/Frisian_Kingdom" title="Frisian Kingdom">Frisian Kingdom</a>. Following the decline of the <a href="/wiki/Duchy_of_Brabant" title="Duchy of Brabant">Duchy of Brabant</a> and the <a href="/wiki/County_of_Flanders" title="County of Flanders">County of Flanders</a>, Holland became the most economically and politically important county in the <a href="/wiki/Low_Countries" title="Low Countries">Low Countries</a> region. The emphasis on Holland during the formation of the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Republic" title="Dutch Republic">Dutch Republic</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Eighty_Years%27_War" title="Eighty Years' War">Eighty Years' War</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/Anglo-Dutch_Wars" title="Anglo-Dutch Wars">Anglo-Dutch Wars</a> in the 16th, 17th, and 18th centuries, made Holland serve as a <i><a href="/wiki/Pars_pro_toto" title="Pars pro toto">pars pro toto</a></i> for the entire country, which is now considered informal<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">[39]</a></sup> or incorrect.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">[40]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">[41]</a></sup> Nonetheless, the name "Holland" is still widely used for the <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_national_football_team" title="Netherlands national football team">Netherlands national football team</a>, including in the Netherlands,<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">[42]</a></sup> and the Dutch government's international websites for tourism and trade are "holland.com" and "hollandtradeandinvest.com".<sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">[43]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">[44]</a></sup> In 2020, however, the Dutch government announced that it would only communicate and advertise under the name "the Netherlands" in the future.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">[45]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Dutch">Dutch</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Dutch">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <p>The term Dutch is used as the demonymic and adjectival form of the Netherlands in the English language. The origins of the word go back to Proto-Germanic <i>*þiudiskaz</i>, <a href="/wiki/Onomastic_Latinisation" class="mw-redirect" title="Onomastic Latinisation">Latinised</a> into <a href="/wiki/Theodiscus" title="Theodiscus">Theodiscus</a>, meaning "popular" or "of the people"; akin to Old Dutch <i>dietsc</i>, Old High German <i>diutsch</i>, and Old English <i>þeodisc</i>, all meaning "(of) the common (Germanic) people". At first, the English language used (the contemporary form of) Dutch to refer to any or all speakers of West Germanic languages (e.g. the Dutch, the Frisians, and the Germans). Gradually its meaning shifted to the West Germanic people they had most contact with, because of their geographical proximity and for the rivalry in trade and overseas territories. The derivative of the Proto-Germanic word <i>*þiudiskaz</i> in modern Dutch, <i>Diets</i>, can be found in Dutch literature as a poetic name for the Dutch people or language, but is considered very archaic. It is still used in the expression "diets maken" – to put it straight to him/her (as in a threat) or, more neutral, to make it clear, understandable, explain, say in the people's language (cf. the Vulgate (Bible not in Greek or Hebrew, but Latin; the folks' language) in meaning vulgar, though not in a pejorative sense). </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Terminology_in_Dutch_and_other_languages">Terminology in Dutch and other languages</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Terminology in Dutch and other languages">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <table class="box-Cleanup plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-style ambox-Cleanup" role="presentation">
       <tbody>
        <tr>
         <td class="mbox-image">
          <div style="width:52px">
           <img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-clear.svg.png" decoding="async" width="40" height="40" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/60px-Edit-clear.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/80px-Edit-clear.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="48" data-file-height="48">
          </div></td>
         <td class="mbox-text">
          <div class="mbox-text-span">
           This section may <b>require <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Cleanup" title="Wikipedia:Cleanup">cleanup</a></b> to meet Wikipedia's <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style">quality standards</a>. The specific problem is: <b>poor referencing, style issues</b><span class="hide-when-compact"> Please help <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit">improve this section</a> if you can.</span> <small class="date-container"><i>(<span class="date">August 2020</span>)</i></small><small class="hide-when-compact"><i> (<a href="/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" title="Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove this template message</a>)</i></small>
          </div></td>
        </tr>
       </tbody>
      </table> 
      <p>In Dutch, the names for the Netherlands, the Dutch language and a Dutch citizen are <i>Nederland</i>, <i>Nederlands</i> and <i>Nederlander</i>. However, colloquially the country is even by the Dutch often referred to as <a href="/wiki/Holland" title="Holland">Holland</a>, although rarely outside the two provinces North and South Holland, where it may even be used as a <a href="/wiki/Pejorative" title="Pejorative">pejorative</a> term, e.g. Hollènder (dialect) in <a href="/wiki/Maastricht" title="Maastricht">Maastricht</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">[46]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The plural <i>Nederlanden</i> is used in many different connotations in the past,<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">[47]</a></sup> but since 1815 it has been used in the official name <i>Koninkrijk der Nederlanden</i> ("<a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_the_Netherlands" title="Kingdom of the Netherlands">Kingdom of the Netherlands</a>"). </p>
      <p>In many other languages, however, the plural stuck, generally preceded by an article, e.g. <i>die Niederlande</i> (<a href="/wiki/German_language" title="German language">German</a>), <i>les Pays-Bas</i> (<a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">French</a>) and <i>los Países Bajos</i> (<a href="/wiki/Spanish_language" title="Spanish language">Spanish</a>). In <a href="/wiki/Indonesian_language" title="Indonesian language">Indonesian</a> (a former colony) the country is called <i>Belanda</i>, a name derived from 'Holland'. </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/History_of_the_Netherlands" title="History of the Netherlands">History of the Netherlands</a>
      </div> 
      <h3><span id="Prehistory_.28before_800_BC.29"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Prehistory_(before_800_BC)">Prehistory (before 800 BC)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Prehistory (before 800 BC)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Paleolithic_Europe" title="Paleolithic Europe">Paleolithic Europe</a>, <a href="/wiki/Neolithic_Europe" title="Neolithic Europe">Neolithic Europe</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Bronze_Age_Europe" title="Bronze Age Europe">Bronze Age Europe</a>
      </div> 
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:152px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Mannetje_van_Willemstad.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/Mannetje_van_Willemstad.jpg/150px-Mannetje_van_Willemstad.jpg" decoding="async" width="150" height="267" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/Mannetje_van_Willemstad.jpg/225px-Mannetje_van_Willemstad.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/Mannetje_van_Willemstad.jpg/300px-Mannetje_van_Willemstad.jpg 2x" data-file-width="620" data-file-height="1104"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Mannetje_van_Willemstad.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Oak figurine found in <a href="/wiki/Willemstad,_North_Brabant" title="Willemstad, North Brabant">Willemstad</a> (4500 BC)
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The prehistory of the area that is now the Netherlands was largely shaped by the sea and the rivers that constantly shifted the low-lying geography. The oldest human (<a href="/wiki/Neanderthal" title="Neanderthal">Neanderthal</a>) traces were found in higher soils, near <a href="/wiki/Maastricht" title="Maastricht">Maastricht</a>, from what is believed to be about 250,000 years ago.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">[48]</a></sup> At the end of the <a href="/wiki/Weichselian_glaciation" title="Weichselian glaciation">Ice Age</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Nomadic" class="mw-redirect" title="Nomadic">nomadic</a> late <a href="/wiki/Upper_Paleolithic" title="Upper Paleolithic">Upper Paleolithic</a> <a href="/wiki/Hamburg_culture" title="Hamburg culture">Hamburg culture</a> (c. 13.000–10.000 BC) hunted <a href="/wiki/Reindeer" title="Reindeer">reindeer</a> in the area, using spears, but the later <a href="/wiki/Ahrensburg_culture" title="Ahrensburg culture">Ahrensburg culture</a> (c. 11.200–9500 BC) used <a href="/wiki/Bow_and_arrow" title="Bow and arrow">bow and arrow</a>. From <a href="/wiki/Mesolithic_Europe" class="mw-redirect" title="Mesolithic Europe">Mesolithic</a> <a href="/wiki/Maglemosian_culture" title="Maglemosian culture">Maglemosian-like tribes</a> (c. 8000 BC) the <a href="/wiki/Pesse_canoe" title="Pesse canoe">oldest canoe</a> in the world was found in <a href="/wiki/Drenthe" title="Drenthe">Drenthe</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">[49]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Indigenous late Mesolithic <a href="/wiki/Hunter-gatherer" title="Hunter-gatherer">hunter-gatherers</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Swifterbant_culture" title="Swifterbant culture">Swifterbant culture</a> (c. 5600 BC) were related to the southern Scandinavian <a href="/wiki/Erteb%C3%B8lle_culture" title="Ertebølle culture">Ertebølle culture</a> and were strongly linked to rivers and open water.<sup id="cite_ref-Kooijmans1998_59-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kooijmans1998-59">[50]</a></sup> Between 4800 and 4500 BC, the Swifterbant people started to copy from the neighbouring <a href="/wiki/Linear_Pottery_culture" title="Linear Pottery culture">Linear Pottery culture</a> the practise of <a href="/wiki/Animal_husbandry" title="Animal husbandry">animal husbandry</a>, and between 4300 and 4000 BC the practice of <a href="/wiki/Agriculture" title="Agriculture">agriculture</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">[51]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Funnelbeaker_culture" title="Funnelbeaker culture">Funnelbeaker culture</a> (c. 4300–2800 BC), which is related to the Swifterbant culture, erected the <a href="/wiki/Dolmens" class="mw-redirect" title="Dolmens">dolmens</a>, large stone grave monuments found in Drenthe. There was a quick and smooth transition from the Funnelbeaker farming culture to the pan-European <a href="/wiki/Corded_Ware" class="mw-redirect" title="Corded Ware">Corded Ware</a> <a href="/wiki/Pastoralism" title="Pastoralism">pastoralist</a> culture (c. 2950 BC). In the southwest, the <a href="/wiki/Seine-Oise-Marne_culture" class="mw-redirect" title="Seine-Oise-Marne culture">Seine-Oise-Marne culture</a> — which was related to the <a href="/wiki/Vlaardingen_culture" title="Vlaardingen culture">Vlaardingen culture</a> (c. 2600 BC), an apparently more primitive culture of hunter-gatherers — survived well into the <a href="/wiki/Neolithic" title="Neolithic">Neolithic</a> period, until it too was succeeded by the Corded Ware culture. </p> 
      <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r978413945/mw-parser-output/.tmulti">.mw-parser-output .tmulti .thumbinner{display:flex;flex-direction:column}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .trow{display:flex;flex-direction:row;clear:left;flex-wrap:wrap;width:100%;box-sizing:border-box}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .tsingle{margin:1px;float:left}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .theader{clear:both;font-weight:bold;text-align:center;align-self:center;background-color:transparent;width:100%}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .thumbcaption{background-color:transparent}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .text-align-left{text-align:left}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .text-align-right{text-align:right}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .text-align-center{text-align:center}@media all and (max-width:720px){.mw-parser-output .tmulti .thumbinner{width:100%!important;box-sizing:border-box;max-width:none!important;align-items:center}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .trow{justify-content:center}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .tsingle{float:none!important;max-width:100%!important;box-sizing:border-box;text-align:center}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .tsingle .thumbcaption{text-align:left}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .trow>.thumbcaption{text-align:center}}</style>
      <div class="thumb tmulti tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:342px;max-width:342px">
        <div class="trow">
         <div class="tsingle" style="width:137px;max-width:137px">
          <div class="thumbimage" style="height:163px;overflow:hidden">
           <a href="/wiki/File:5500vc_ex_leg.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/5500vc_ex_leg.jpg/135px-5500vc_ex_leg.jpg" decoding="async" width="135" height="163" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/5500vc_ex_leg.jpg/203px-5500vc_ex_leg.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/5500vc_ex_leg.jpg/270px-5500vc_ex_leg.jpg 2x" data-file-width="510" data-file-height="616"></a>
          </div>
          <div class="thumbcaption text-align-center">
           The Netherlands in 5500 BC
          </div>
         </div>
         <div class="tsingle" style="width:201px;max-width:201px">
          <div class="thumbimage" style="height:163px;overflow:hidden">
           <a href="/wiki/File:BronzAgeElp.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/BronzAgeElp.png/199px-BronzAgeElp.png" decoding="async" width="199" height="163" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/BronzAgeElp.png/299px-BronzAgeElp.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/BronzAgeElp.png/398px-BronzAgeElp.png 2x" data-file-width="606" data-file-height="497"></a>
          </div>
          <div class="thumbcaption text-align-center">
           Bronze Age cultures in the Netherlands
          </div>
         </div>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>Of the subsequent <a href="/wiki/Beaker_culture" class="mw-redirect" title="Beaker culture">Bell Beaker culture</a> (2700–2100 BC) several regions of origin have been postulated, notably the Iberian peninsula, the Netherlands and Central Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">[52]</a></sup> They introduced metalwork in copper, gold and later bronze and opened international trade routes not seen before, reflected in the discoveries of <a href="/wiki/Copper_Age_Europe" class="mw-redirect" title="Copper Age Europe">copper artifacts</a>, as the metal is not normally found in Dutch soil. The many finds in <a href="/wiki/Drenthe" title="Drenthe">Drenthe</a> of rare bronze objects, suggest that it was even a trading centre in the Bronze Age (2000–800 BC). The Bell Beaker culture developed locally into the Barbed-Wire Beaker culture (2100–1800 BC) and later the <a href="/wiki/Elp_culture" title="Elp culture">Elp culture</a> (c. 1800–800 BC),<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62">[53]</a></sup> a Middle Bronze Age archaeological culture having <a href="/wiki/Earthenware" title="Earthenware">earthenware</a> pottery of low quality as a marker. The initial phase of the Elp culture was characterised by <a href="/wiki/Tumulus" title="Tumulus">tumuli</a> (1800–1200 BC) that were strongly tied to contemporary tumuli in northern Germany and Scandinavia, and were apparently related to the <a href="/wiki/Tumulus_culture" title="Tumulus culture">Tumulus culture</a> in central Europe. The subsequent phase was that of cremating the dead and placing their ashes in urns which were then buried in fields, following the customs of the <a href="/wiki/Urnfield_culture" title="Urnfield culture">Urnfield culture</a> (1200–800 BC). The southern region became dominated by the related <a href="/wiki/Hilversum_culture" title="Hilversum culture">Hilversum culture</a> (1800–800 BC), which apparently inherited cultural ties with Britain of the previous Barbed-Wire Beaker culture. </p> 
      <h3><span id="Celts.2C_Germanic_tribes_and_Romans_.28800_BC.E2.80.93410_AD.29"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Celts,_Germanic_tribes_and_Romans_(800_BC–410_AD)">Celts, Germanic tribes and Romans (800 BC–410 AD)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Celts, Germanic tribes and Romans (800 BC–410 AD)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Iron_Age_Europe" title="Iron Age Europe">Iron Age Europe</a>, <a href="/wiki/Celts" title="Celts">Celts</a>, <a href="/wiki/Germanic_peoples" title="Germanic peoples">Germanic peoples</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_in_the_Roman_era" title="Netherlands in the Roman era">Netherlands in the Roman era</a>
      </div> 
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:152px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Celtic_expansion_in_Europe.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Celtic_expansion_in_Europe.svg/150px-Celtic_expansion_in_Europe.svg.png" decoding="async" width="150" height="111" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Celtic_expansion_in_Europe.svg/225px-Celtic_expansion_in_Europe.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Celtic_expansion_in_Europe.svg/300px-Celtic_expansion_in_Europe.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="933" data-file-height="690"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Celtic_expansion_in_Europe.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>
         <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r981673959">.mw-parser-output .legend{page-break-inside:avoid;break-inside:avoid-column}.mw-parser-output .legend-color{display:inline-block;min-width:1.25em;height:1.25em;line-height:1.25;margin:1px 0;text-align:center;border:1px solid black;background-color:transparent;color:black}.mw-parser-output .legend-text{}</style>
         <div class="legend">
          <span class="legend-color" style="background-color:#FFFF43; color:black;">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;<a href="/wiki/Historical_linguistics" title="Historical linguistics">Diachronic</a> distribution of <a href="/wiki/Celts" title="Celts">Celts</a> from 500 BC
         </div>
         <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959">
         <div class="legend">
          <span class="legend-color" style="background-color:#97FFB6; color:black;">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;Expansion into the southern <a href="/wiki/Low_Countries" title="Low Countries">Low Countries</a> by 270 BC
         </div>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>From 800 BC onwards, the <a href="/wiki/Iron_Age_Europe" title="Iron Age Europe">Iron Age</a> Celtic <a href="/wiki/Hallstatt_culture" title="Hallstatt culture">Hallstatt culture</a> became influential, replacing the <a href="/wiki/Hilversum_culture" title="Hilversum culture">Hilversum culture</a>. Iron ore brought a measure of prosperity, and was available throughout the country, including <a href="/wiki/Bog_iron" title="Bog iron">bog iron</a>. <a href="/wiki/Blacksmith" title="Blacksmith">Smiths</a> travelled from settlement to settlement with bronze and iron, fabricating tools on demand. The <a href="/wiki/Vorstengraf_(Oss)" title="Vorstengraf (Oss)">King's grave of Oss</a> (700 BC) was found in a burial mound, the largest of its kind in western Europe and containing an iron sword with an inlay of gold and coral. </p>
      <p>The deteriorating climate in Scandinavia around 850 BC further deteriorated around 650 BC and might have triggered migration of <a href="/wiki/Germanic_peoples" title="Germanic peoples">Germanic</a> tribes from the North. By the time this migration was complete, around 250 BC, a few general cultural and linguistic groups had emerged.<sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">[54]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Verhaal_64-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Verhaal-64">[55]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/North_Sea_Germanic" title="North Sea Germanic">North Sea Germanic</a> <a href="/wiki/Ingaevones" title="Ingaevones">Ingaevones</a> inhabited the northern part of the <a href="/wiki/Low_Countries" title="Low Countries">Low Countries</a>. They would later develop into the <a href="/wiki/Frisii" title="Frisii">Frisii</a> and the early <a href="/wiki/Saxons" title="Saxons">Saxons</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Verhaal_64-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Verhaal-64">[55]</a></sup> A second grouping, the <a href="/wiki/Weser-Rhine_Germanic" title="Weser-Rhine Germanic">Weser-Rhine Germanic</a> (or <a href="/wiki/Istvaeones" title="Istvaeones">Istvaeones</a>), extended along the middle Rhine and <a href="/wiki/Weser" title="Weser">Weser</a> and inhabited the Low Countries south of the great rivers. This group consisted of tribes that would eventually develop into the <a href="/wiki/Salian_Franks" title="Salian Franks">Salian Franks</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Verhaal_64-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Verhaal-64">[55]</a></sup> Also the <a href="/wiki/Celts" title="Celts">Celtic</a> <a href="/wiki/La_T%C3%A8ne_culture" title="La Tène culture">La Tène culture</a> (c. 450 BC up to the Roman conquest) had expanded over a wide range, including the southern area of the <a href="/wiki/Low_Countries" title="Low Countries">Low Countries</a>. Some scholars have speculated that even a third ethnic identity and language, neither Germanic nor Celtic, survived in the Netherlands until the Roman period, the Iron Age <a href="/wiki/Nordwestblock" title="Nordwestblock">Nordwestblock</a> culture,<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">[56]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Lendering_66-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lendering-66">[57]</a></sup> that eventually was absorbed by the <a href="/wiki/Celts" title="Celts">Celts</a> to the south and the Germanic peoples from the east. </p> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Germania_70.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Germania_70.svg/220px-Germania_70.svg.png" decoding="async" width="220" height="177" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Germania_70.svg/330px-Germania_70.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Germania_70.svg/440px-Germania_70.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="972" data-file-height="780"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Germania_70.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>The Rhine frontier around 70 AD
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The first author to describe the coast of <a href="/wiki/Holland" title="Holland">Holland</a> and <a href="/wiki/Flanders" title="Flanders">Flanders</a> was the <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title="Ancient Greece">Greek</a> <a href="/wiki/Geographer" title="Geographer">geographer</a> <a href="/wiki/Pytheas" title="Pytheas">Pytheas</a>, who noted in c.325 BC that in these regions, "more people died in the struggle against water than in the struggle against men."<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67">[58]</a></sup> During the <a href="/wiki/Gallic_Wars" title="Gallic Wars">Gallic Wars</a>, the area south and west of the <a href="/wiki/Rhine" title="Rhine">Rhine</a> was conquered by <a href="/wiki/Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">Roman forces</a> under <a href="/wiki/Julius_Caesar" title="Julius Caesar">Julius Caesar</a> from 57 BC to 53 BC.<sup id="cite_ref-Lendering_66-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lendering-66">[57]</a></sup> Caesar describes two main Celtic tribes living in what is now the southern Netherlands: the <a href="/wiki/Menapii" title="Menapii">Menapii</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Eburones" title="Eburones">Eburones</a>. The Rhine became fixed as Rome's northern frontier around 12 AD. Notable towns would arise along the <a href="/wiki/Limes_Germanicus" title="Limes Germanicus">Limes Germanicus</a>: <a href="/wiki/Nijmegen" title="Nijmegen">Nijmegen</a> and <a href="/wiki/Voorburg" title="Voorburg">Voorburg</a>. At first part of <a href="/wiki/Gallia_Belgica" title="Gallia Belgica">Gallia Belgica</a>, the area south of the Limes became part of the <a href="/wiki/Roman_province" title="Roman province">Roman province</a> of <a href="/wiki/Germania_Inferior" title="Germania Inferior">Germania Inferior</a>. The area to the north of the Rhine, inhabited by the Frisii, remained outside Roman rule (but not its presence and control), while the Germanic border tribes of the <a href="/wiki/Batavi_(Germanic_tribe)" title="Batavi (Germanic tribe)">Batavi</a> and <a href="/wiki/Cananefates" title="Cananefates">Cananefates</a> served in the <a href="/wiki/Ala_(Roman_allied_military_unit)" title="Ala (Roman allied military unit)">Roman cavalry</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">[59]</a></sup> The Batavi rose against the Romans in the <a href="/wiki/Revolt_of_the_Batavi" title="Revolt of the Batavi">Batavian rebellion</a> of 69 AD, but were eventually defeated. The Batavi later merged with other tribes into the confederation of the Salian Franks, whose identity emerged at the first half of the third century.<sup id="cite_ref-Previté-Orton_69-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Previté-Orton-69">[60]</a></sup> Salian Franks appear in Roman texts as both allies and enemies. They were forced by the confederation of the Saxons from the east to move over the Rhine into Roman territory in the fourth century. From their new base in <a href="/wiki/West_Flanders" title="West Flanders">West Flanders</a> and the Southwest Netherlands, they were raiding the <a href="/wiki/English_Channel" title="English Channel">English Channel</a>. Roman forces pacified the region, but did not expel the Franks, who continued to be feared at least until the time of <a href="/wiki/Julian_(emperor)" title="Julian (emperor)">Julian the Apostate</a> (358), when Salian Franks were allowed to settle as <i><a href="/wiki/Foederati" title="Foederati">foederati</a></i> in <a href="/wiki/Texandria" title="Texandria">Texandria</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Previté-Orton_69-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Previté-Orton-69">[60]</a></sup> It has been postulated that after deteriorating climate conditions and the Romans' withdrawal, the <a href="/wiki/Frisii" title="Frisii">Frisii</a> disappeared as <i><a href="/wiki/Laeti" title="Laeti">laeti</a></i> in c. 296, leaving the coastal lands largely unpopulated for the next two centuries.<sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">[61]</a></sup> However, recent excavations in <a href="/wiki/Kennemerland" title="Kennemerland">Kennemerland</a> show clear indication of a permanent habitation.<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71">[62]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">[63]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span id="Early_Middle_Ages_.28411.E2.80.931000.29"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Early_Middle_Ages_(411–1000)">Early Middle Ages (411–1000)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Early Middle Ages (411–1000)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Frankish_Kingdom" class="mw-redirect" title="Frankish Kingdom">Frankish Kingdom</a> and <a href="/wiki/Frisian_Kingdom" title="Frisian Kingdom">Frisian Kingdom</a>
      </div> 
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Frisia_716-la.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Frisia_716-la.svg/170px-Frisia_716-la.svg.png" decoding="async" width="170" height="176" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Frisia_716-la.svg/255px-Frisia_716-la.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Frisia_716-la.svg/340px-Frisia_716-la.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="583" data-file-height="602"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Frisia_716-la.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Franks, Frisians and Saxons (710s AD)
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>After <a href="/wiki/Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">Roman</a> government in the area collapsed, the Franks expanded their territories in numerous kingdoms. By the 490s, <a href="/wiki/Clovis_I" title="Clovis I">Clovis I</a> had conquered and united all these territories in the southern Netherlands in one <a href="/wiki/Frankish_kingdom" class="mw-redirect" title="Frankish kingdom">Frankish kingdom</a>, and from there continued his conquests into <a href="/wiki/Gaul" title="Gaul">Gaul</a>. During this expansion, Franks migrating to the south eventually adopted the <a href="/wiki/Vulgar_Latin" title="Vulgar Latin">Vulgar Latin</a> of the local population.<sup id="cite_ref-Verhaal_64-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Verhaal-64">[55]</a></sup> A widening cultural divide grew with the Franks remaining in their original homeland in the north (i.e. southern Netherlands and Flanders), who kept on speaking <a href="/wiki/Old_Frankish" class="mw-redirect" title="Old Frankish">Old Frankish</a>, which by the ninth century had evolved into <a href="/wiki/Old_Low_Franconian" class="mw-redirect" title="Old Low Franconian">Old Low Franconian</a> or <a href="/wiki/Old_Dutch" title="Old Dutch">Old Dutch</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Verhaal_64-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Verhaal-64">[55]</a></sup> A Dutch-French language boundary hence came into existence.<sup id="cite_ref-Verhaal_64-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Verhaal-64">[55]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73">[64]</a></sup> </p> 
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Franks_expansion.gif" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Franks_expansion.gif/170px-Franks_expansion.gif" decoding="async" width="170" height="109" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Franks_expansion.gif/255px-Franks_expansion.gif 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Franks_expansion.gif/340px-Franks_expansion.gif 2x" data-file-width="790" data-file-height="505"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Franks_expansion.gif" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Frankish expansion (481 to 870 AD)
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>To the north of the Franks, climatic conditions improved, and during the <a href="/wiki/Migration_Period" title="Migration Period">Migration Period</a> <a href="/wiki/Saxons" title="Saxons">Saxons</a>, the closely related <a href="/wiki/Angles" title="Angles">Angles</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jutes" title="Jutes">Jutes</a> and <a href="/wiki/Frisii" title="Frisii">Frisii</a> settled the coastal land.<sup id="cite_ref-Ethnic_Constructs_in_Antiquity_74-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ethnic_Constructs_in_Antiquity-74">[65]</a></sup> Many moved on to <a href="/wiki/England" title="England">England</a> and came to be known as <a href="/wiki/Anglo-Saxons" title="Anglo-Saxons">Anglo-Saxons</a>, but those who stayed would be referred to as <a href="/wiki/Frisians" title="Frisians">Frisians</a> and their language as <a href="/wiki/Frisian_languages" title="Frisian languages">Frisian</a>, named after the land that was once inhabited by Frisii.<sup id="cite_ref-Ethnic_Constructs_in_Antiquity_74-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ethnic_Constructs_in_Antiquity-74">[65]</a></sup> Frisian was spoken along the entire southern North Sea coast, and it is still the language most closely related to English among the living languages of continental Europe. By the seventh century a <a href="/wiki/Frisian_Kingdom" title="Frisian Kingdom">Frisian Kingdom</a> (650–734) under King <a href="/wiki/Aldegisel" class="mw-redirect" title="Aldegisel">Aldegisel</a> and King <a href="/wiki/Redbad,_King_of_the_Frisians" title="Redbad, King of the Frisians">Redbad</a> emerged with <a href="/wiki/Utrecht_(city)" class="mw-redirect" title="Utrecht (city)">Utrecht</a> as its centre of power,<sup id="cite_ref-Ethnic_Constructs_in_Antiquity_74-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ethnic_Constructs_in_Antiquity-74">[65]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75">[66]</a></sup> while <a href="/wiki/Dorestad" title="Dorestad">Dorestad</a> was a flourishing trading place.<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">[67]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Atlas_77-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Atlas-77">[68]</a></sup> Between 600 and around 719 the cities were often fought over between the Frisians and the Franks. In 734, at the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_the_Boarn" title="Battle of the Boarn">Battle of the Boarn</a>, the Frisians were defeated after a <a href="/wiki/Frisian%E2%80%93Frankish_wars" title="Frisian–Frankish wars">series of wars</a>. With the approval of the Franks, the <a href="/wiki/Anglo-Saxon_mission" title="Anglo-Saxon mission">Anglo-Saxon</a> missionary <a href="/wiki/Willibrord" title="Willibrord">Willibrord</a> converted the Frisian people to <a href="/wiki/Christianity" title="Christianity">Christianity</a>. He established the <a href="/wiki/Archdiocese_of_Utrecht_(695%E2%80%931580)" class="mw-redirect" title="Archdiocese of Utrecht (695–1580)">Archdiocese of Utrecht</a> and became bishop of the Frisians. However, his successor <a href="/wiki/Boniface" class="mw-redirect" title="Boniface">Boniface</a> was murdered by the Frisians in <a href="/wiki/Dokkum" title="Dokkum">Dokkum</a>, in 754. </p> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Rorik_by_H._W._Koekkoek.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Rorik_by_H._W._Koekkoek.jpg/220px-Rorik_by_H._W._Koekkoek.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="309" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Rorik_by_H._W._Koekkoek.jpg/330px-Rorik_by_H._W._Koekkoek.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Rorik_by_H._W._Koekkoek.jpg/440px-Rorik_by_H._W._Koekkoek.jpg 2x" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="843"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Rorik_by_H._W._Koekkoek.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div><a href="/wiki/Rorik_of_Dorestad" title="Rorik of Dorestad">Rorik of Dorestad</a>, <a href="/wiki/Viking" class="mw-redirect" title="Viking">Viking</a> ruler of <a href="/wiki/Friesland" title="Friesland">Friesland</a> (romantic 1912 depiction)
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The Frankish <a href="/wiki/Carolingian_empire" class="mw-redirect" title="Carolingian empire">Carolingian empire</a> modeled itself after the Roman Empire and controlled much of Western Europe. However, as of 843, it was divided into three parts—<a href="/wiki/East_Francia" title="East Francia">East</a>, <a href="/wiki/Middle_Francia" title="Middle Francia">Middle</a>, and <a href="/wiki/West_Francia" title="West Francia">West Francia</a>. Most of present-day Netherlands became part of <a href="/wiki/Middle_Francia" title="Middle Francia">Middle Francia</a>, which was a weak kingdom and subject of numerous partitions and annexation attempts by its stronger neighbours. It comprised territories from <a href="/wiki/Frisia" title="Frisia">Frisia</a> in the north to the <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_Italy_(medieval)" class="mw-redirect" title="Kingdom of Italy (medieval)">Kingdom of Italy</a> in the south. Around 850, <a href="/wiki/Lothair_I" title="Lothair I">Lothair I</a> of Middle Francia acknowledged the Viking <a href="/wiki/Rorik_of_Dorestad" title="Rorik of Dorestad">Rorik of Dorestad</a> as ruler of most of Frisia.<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">[69]</a></sup> When the kingdom of Middle Francia was partitioned in 855, the lands north of the <a href="/wiki/Alps" title="Alps">Alps</a> passed to <a href="/wiki/Lothair_II_of_Lotharingia" class="mw-redirect" title="Lothair II of Lotharingia">Lothair II</a> and subsequently were named <a href="/wiki/Lotharingia" title="Lotharingia">Lotharingia</a>. After he died in 869, Lotharingia was partitioned, into <a href="/wiki/Upper_Lotharingia" class="mw-redirect" title="Upper Lotharingia">Upper</a> and <a href="/wiki/Lower_Lotharingia" title="Lower Lotharingia">Lower Lotharingia</a>, the latter part comprising the Low Countries that technically became part of <a href="/wiki/East_Francia" title="East Francia">East Francia</a> in 870, although it was effectively under the control of Vikings, who raided the largely defenceless <a href="/wiki/Frisians" title="Frisians">Frisian</a> and <a href="/wiki/Franks" title="Franks">Frankish</a> towns lying on the Frisian coast and along the rivers. Around 879, another Viking expedition led by <a href="/wiki/Godfrid,_Duke_of_Frisia" title="Godfrid, Duke of Frisia">Godfrid, Duke of Frisia</a> raided the Frisian lands. The Viking raids made the sway of French and German lords in the area weak. Resistance to the Vikings, if any, came from local nobles, who gained in stature as a result, and that laid the basis for the disintegration of Lower Lotharingia into semi-independent states. One of these local nobles was <a href="/wiki/Gerolf_of_Holland" title="Gerolf of Holland">Gerolf of Holland</a>, who assumed lordship in Frisia after he helped to assassinate Godfrid, and Viking rule came to an end. </p> 
      <h3><span id="High_Middle_Ages_.281000.E2.80.931384.29"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="High_Middle_Ages_(1000–1384)">High Middle Ages (1000–1384)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: High Middle Ages (1000–1384)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Graftombe_Ridder_Arnold_van_der_Sluijs.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Graftombe_Ridder_Arnold_van_der_Sluijs.jpg/220px-Graftombe_Ridder_Arnold_van_der_Sluijs.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="197" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Graftombe_Ridder_Arnold_van_der_Sluijs.jpg/330px-Graftombe_Ridder_Arnold_van_der_Sluijs.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Graftombe_Ridder_Arnold_van_der_Sluijs.jpg/440px-Graftombe_Ridder_Arnold_van_der_Sluijs.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1115" data-file-height="1000"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Graftombe_Ridder_Arnold_van_der_Sluijs.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>A Medieval Tombe of the Brabantian Knight Arnold van der Sluijs
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/History_of_urban_centers_in_the_Low_Countries" title="History of urban centers in the Low Countries">History of urban centers in the Low Countries</a>
      </div> 
      <p>The <a href="/wiki/Holy_Roman_Empire" title="Holy Roman Empire">Holy Roman Empire</a> (the successor state of East Francia and then Lotharingia) ruled much of the Low Countries in the 10th and 11th century, but was not able to maintain political unity. Powerful local nobles turned their cities, counties and duchies into private kingdoms that felt little sense of obligation to the emperor. <a href="/wiki/County_of_Holland" title="County of Holland">Holland</a>, <a href="/wiki/County_of_Hainaut" title="County of Hainaut">Hainaut</a>, <a href="/wiki/County_of_Flanders" title="County of Flanders">Flanders</a>, <a href="/wiki/Duchy_of_Gelre" class="mw-redirect" title="Duchy of Gelre">Gelre</a>, <a href="/wiki/Duchy_of_Brabant" title="Duchy of Brabant">Brabant</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Bishopric_of_Utrecht" class="mw-redirect" title="Bishopric of Utrecht">Utrecht</a> were in a state of almost continual war or in paradoxically formed personal unions. The language and culture of most of the people who lived in the County of Holland were originally <a href="/wiki/Frisia" title="Frisia">Frisian</a>. As Frankish settlement progressed from Flanders and Brabant, the area quickly became <a href="/wiki/Old_Low_Franconian" class="mw-redirect" title="Old Low Franconian">Old Low Franconian</a> (or <a href="/wiki/Old_Dutch" title="Old Dutch">Old Dutch</a>). The rest of <a href="/wiki/Frisia" title="Frisia">Frisia</a> in the north (now <a href="/wiki/Friesland" title="Friesland">Friesland</a> and <a href="/wiki/Groningen_(province)" title="Groningen (province)">Groningen</a>) continued to maintain its independence and had its own institutions (collectively called the "<a href="/wiki/Frisian_freedom" title="Frisian freedom">Frisian freedom</a>"), which resented the imposition of the feudal system. </p>
      <p>Around 1000 AD, due to several agricultural developments, the economy started to develop at a fast pace, and the higher productivity allowed workers to farm more land or to become tradesmen. Towns grew around <a href="/wiki/Monasteries" class="mw-redirect" title="Monasteries">monasteries</a> and <a href="/wiki/Castles" class="mw-redirect" title="Castles">castles</a>, and a mercantile middle class began to develop in these urban areas, especially in Flanders and later also Brabant. Wealthy cities started to buy certain <a href="/wiki/City_rights_in_the_Low_Countries" title="City rights in the Low Countries">privileges</a> for themselves from the <a href="/wiki/Monarch" title="Monarch">sovereign</a>. In practice, this meant that <a href="/wiki/Brugge" class="mw-redirect" title="Brugge">Brugge</a> and <a href="/wiki/Antwerp" title="Antwerp">Antwerp</a> became quasi-independent republics in their own right and would later develop into some of the most important cities and ports in Europe. </p>
      <p>Around 1100 AD, farmers from <a href="/wiki/County_of_Flanders" title="County of Flanders">Flanders</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bishopric_of_Utrecht" class="mw-redirect" title="Bishopric of Utrecht">Utrecht</a> began draining and cultivating uninhabited swampy land in the western Netherlands, making the emergence of the County of Holland as the centre of power possible. The title of <a href="/wiki/Count_of_Holland" title="Count of Holland">Count of Holland</a> was fought over in the <a href="/wiki/Hook_and_Cod_Wars" class="mw-redirect" title="Hook and Cod Wars">Hook and Cod Wars</a> (<a href="/wiki/Dutch_language" title="Dutch language">Dutch</a>: <i lang="nl">Hoekse en Kabeljauwse twisten</i>) between 1350 and 1490. The Cod faction consisted of the more progressive cities, while the Hook faction consisted of the conservative noblemen. These noblemen invited the Duke <a href="/wiki/Philip_the_Good" title="Philip the Good">Philip the Good</a> of Burgundy — who was also Count of Flanders — to conquer Holland. </p> 
      <h3><span id="Burgundian.2C_Habsburg_and_Spanish_Habsburg_Netherlands_.281384.E2.80.931581.29"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Burgundian,_Habsburg_and_Spanish_Habsburg_Netherlands_(1384–1581)">Burgundian, Habsburg and Spanish Habsburg Netherlands (1384–1581)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Burgundian, Habsburg and Spanish Habsburg Netherlands (1384–1581)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Burgundian_Netherlands" title="Burgundian Netherlands">Burgundian Netherlands</a>, <a href="/wiki/Habsburg_Netherlands" title="Habsburg Netherlands">Habsburg Netherlands</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Spanish_Netherlands" title="Spanish Netherlands">Spanish Netherlands</a>
      </div> 
      <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r978413945/mw-parser-output/.tmulti">
      <div class="thumb tmulti tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:242px;max-width:242px">
        <div class="trow">
         <div class="theader">
          Spanish Netherlands
         </div>
        </div>
        <div class="trow">
         <div class="tsingle" style="width:240px;max-width:240px">
          <div class="thumbimage" style="height:175px;overflow:hidden">
           <a href="/wiki/File:Van_Soest,_Four_Days_Battle.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Van_Soest%2C_Four_Days_Battle.jpg/238px-Van_Soest%2C_Four_Days_Battle.jpg" decoding="async" width="238" height="175" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Van_Soest%2C_Four_Days_Battle.jpg/357px-Van_Soest%2C_Four_Days_Battle.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Van_Soest%2C_Four_Days_Battle.jpg/476px-Van_Soest%2C_Four_Days_Battle.jpg 2x" data-file-width="700" data-file-height="516"></a>
          </div>
          <div class="thumbcaption text-align-center">
           <i>The <a href="/wiki/Four_Days%27_Battle" title="Four Days' Battle">Four Days' Battle</a>, 1–4 June 1666</i> (<a href="/wiki/Second_Anglo-Dutch_War" title="Second Anglo-Dutch War">Second Anglo-Dutch War</a>) by <a href="/wiki/Pieter_Cornelisz_van_Soest" title="Pieter Cornelisz van Soest">Pieter Cornelisz van Soest</a>
          </div>
         </div>
        </div>
        <div class="trow">
         <div class="tsingle" style="width:123px;max-width:123px">
          <div class="thumbimage" style="height:155px;overflow:hidden">
           <a href="/wiki/File:Political_map_of_the_Low_Countries_(1350)-NL.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Political_map_of_the_Low_Countries_%281350%29-NL.svg/121px-Political_map_of_the_Low_Countries_%281350%29-NL.svg.png" decoding="async" width="121" height="155" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Political_map_of_the_Low_Countries_%281350%29-NL.svg/182px-Political_map_of_the_Low_Countries_%281350%29-NL.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Political_map_of_the_Low_Countries_%281350%29-NL.svg/242px-Political_map_of_the_Low_Countries_%281350%29-NL.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="2818" data-file-height="3608"></a>
          </div>
          <div class="thumbcaption text-align-center">
           The Low Countries in the late 14th century
          </div>
         </div>
         <div class="tsingle" style="width:115px;max-width:115px">
          <div class="thumbimage" style="height:155px;overflow:hidden">
           <a href="/wiki/File:William_I,_Prince_of_Orange_by_Adriaen_Thomasz._Key_Rijksmuseum_Amsterdam_SK-A-3148.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/William_I%2C_Prince_of_Orange_by_Adriaen_Thomasz._Key_Rijksmuseum_Amsterdam_SK-A-3148.jpg/113px-William_I%2C_Prince_of_Orange_by_Adriaen_Thomasz._Key_Rijksmuseum_Amsterdam_SK-A-3148.jpg" decoding="async" width="113" height="156" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/William_I%2C_Prince_of_Orange_by_Adriaen_Thomasz._Key_Rijksmuseum_Amsterdam_SK-A-3148.jpg/170px-William_I%2C_Prince_of_Orange_by_Adriaen_Thomasz._Key_Rijksmuseum_Amsterdam_SK-A-3148.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/William_I%2C_Prince_of_Orange_by_Adriaen_Thomasz._Key_Rijksmuseum_Amsterdam_SK-A-3148.jpg/226px-William_I%2C_Prince_of_Orange_by_Adriaen_Thomasz._Key_Rijksmuseum_Amsterdam_SK-A-3148.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4876" data-file-height="6728"></a>
          </div>
          <div class="thumbcaption text-align-center">
           <a href="/wiki/William_the_Silent" title="William the Silent">William I</a>, Prince of Orange, leader of the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Revolt" title="Dutch Revolt">Dutch Revolt</a> by <a href="/wiki/Adriaen_Thomasz._Key" class="mw-redirect" title="Adriaen Thomasz. Key">Adriaen Thomasz. Key</a>
          </div>
         </div>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p><br> Most of the <a href="/wiki/Holy_Roman_Empire" title="Holy Roman Empire">Imperial</a> and <a href="/wiki/France_in_the_Middle_Ages" title="France in the Middle Ages">French</a> fiefs in what is now the Netherlands and Belgium were united in a <a href="/wiki/Personal_union" title="Personal union">personal union</a> by Philip the Good, Duke of <a href="/wiki/Duchy_of_Burgundy" title="Duchy of Burgundy">Burgundy</a> in 1433. The <a href="/wiki/House_of_Valois-Burgundy" title="House of Valois-Burgundy">House of Valois-Burgundy</a> and their <a href="/wiki/House_of_Habsburg" title="House of Habsburg">Habsburg</a> heirs would rule the Low Countries in the period from 1384 to 1581. Before the Burgundian union, the Dutch identified themselves by the town they lived in or their local duchy or county. The Burgundian period is when the road to nationhood began. The new rulers defended Dutch trading interests, which then developed rapidly. The fleets of the <a href="/wiki/County_of_Holland" title="County of Holland">County of Holland</a> defeated the fleets of the <a href="/wiki/Hanseatic_League" title="Hanseatic League">Hanseatic League</a> several times. <a href="/wiki/Amsterdam" title="Amsterdam">Amsterdam</a> grew and in the 15th century became the primary trading port in Europe for grain from the <a href="/wiki/Baltic_region" title="Baltic region">Baltic region</a>. Amsterdam distributed grain to the major cities of Belgium, Northern France and England. This trade was vital, because Holland could no longer produce enough grain to feed itself. Land drainage had caused the <a href="/wiki/Peat" title="Peat">peat</a> of the former <a href="/wiki/Wetland" title="Wetland">wetlands</a> to reduce to a level that was too low for drainage to be maintained. </p>
      <p>Under Habsburg <a href="/wiki/Charles_V,_Holy_Roman_Emperor" title="Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor">Charles V</a>, ruler of the <a href="/wiki/Holy_Roman_Empire" title="Holy Roman Empire">Holy Roman Empire</a> and King of <a href="/wiki/Habsburg_Spain" title="Habsburg Spain">Spain</a>, all fiefs in the current Netherlands region were united into the <a href="/wiki/Seventeen_Provinces" title="Seventeen Provinces">Seventeen Provinces</a>, which also included most of present-day Belgium, Luxembourg, and some adjacent land in what is now France and Germany. In 1568, under Phillip II, the <a href="/wiki/Eighty_Years%27_War" title="Eighty Years' War">Eighty Years' War</a> between the Provinces and their <a href="/wiki/Spanish_Empire" title="Spanish Empire">Spanish</a> ruler began. The level of ferocity exhibited by both sides can be gleaned from a Dutch chronicler's report:<sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">[70]</a></sup> </p> 
      <blockquote>
       <p> On more than one occasion men were seen hanging their own brothers, who had been taken prisoners in the enemy's ranks.... A Spaniard had ceased to be human in their eyes. On one occasion, a surgeon at Veer cut the heart from a Spanish prisoner, nailed it on a vessel's prow, and invited the townsmen to come and fasten their teeth in it, which many did with savage satisfaction. </p>
      </blockquote> 
      <p>The <a href="/wiki/Fernando_%C3%81lvarez_de_Toledo,_3rd_Duke_of_Alba" title="Fernando Álvarez de Toledo, 3rd Duke of Alba">Duke of Alba</a> ruthlessly attempted to suppress the Protestant movement in the Netherlands. Netherlanders were "burned, strangled, beheaded, or buried alive" by his "<a href="/wiki/Council_of_Troubles" title="Council of Troubles">Blood Council</a>" and his Spanish soldiers. Severed heads and decapitated corpses were displayed along streets and roads to terrorize the population into submission. Alba boasted of having executed 18,600,<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80">[71]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">[72]</a></sup> but this figure does not include those who perished by war and famine. </p>
      <p>The first great siege was Alba's effort to capture <a href="/wiki/Haarlem" title="Haarlem">Haarlem</a> and thereby cut Holland in half. It dragged on from December 1572 to the next summer, when Haarlemers finally surrendered on 13 July upon promise that the city would be spared from being sacked. It was a stipulation <a href="/wiki/Fadrique_%C3%81lvarez_de_Toledo,_4th_Duke_of_Alba" title="Fadrique Álvarez de Toledo, 4th Duke of Alba">Don Fadrique</a> was unable to honor, when his soldiers mutinied, angered over pay owed and the miserable conditions they endured during the long, cold months of the campaign.<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">[73]</a></sup> On 4 November 1576, Spanish <a href="/wiki/Tercio" title="Tercio">tercios</a> seized <a href="/wiki/Antwerp" title="Antwerp">Antwerp</a> and subjected it to the worst pillage in the Netherlands' history. The citizens resisted, but were overcome; seven thousand of them were mowed down; a thousand buildings were torched; men, women, and children were slaughtered in a delirium of blood by soldiers crying, "Santiago! España! A sangre, a carne, a fuego, a sacco!" (Saint James! Spain! To blood, to the flesh, to fire, to sack!)<sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">[74]</a></sup> </p> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Habsburg_Map_1547.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Habsburg_Map_1547.jpg/220px-Habsburg_Map_1547.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="137" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Habsburg_Map_1547.jpg/330px-Habsburg_Map_1547.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Habsburg_Map_1547.jpg/440px-Habsburg_Map_1547.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1654" data-file-height="1029"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Habsburg_Map_1547.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Map of the <a href="/wiki/Habsburg_Monarchy" title="Habsburg Monarchy">Habsburg</a> dominions. From 1556 the dynasty's lands in the <a href="/wiki/Low_Countries" title="Low Countries">Low Countries</a> were retained by the <a href="/wiki/Spanish_Habsburgs" class="mw-redirect" title="Spanish Habsburgs">Spanish Habsburgs</a>.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
