      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Foreign_relations">Foreign relations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=28" title="Edit section: Foreign relations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Foreign_relations_of_the_Netherlands" title="Foreign relations of the Netherlands">Foreign relations of the Netherlands</a> and <a href="/wiki/List_of_diplomatic_missions_of_the_Netherlands" title="List of diplomatic missions of the Netherlands">List of diplomatic missions of the Netherlands</a>
      </div> 
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:International_Court_of_Justice.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/International_Court_of_Justice.jpg/220px-International_Court_of_Justice.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="164" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/International_Court_of_Justice.jpg/330px-International_Court_of_Justice.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/International_Court_of_Justice.jpg/440px-International_Court_of_Justice.jpg 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="597"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:International_Court_of_Justice.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>The <a href="/wiki/Peace_Palace" title="Peace Palace">Peace Palace</a> (<i>Vredespaleis</i>), in <a href="/wiki/The_Hague" title="The Hague">The Hague</a>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The history of <a href="/wiki/Foreign_relations_of_the_Netherlands" title="Foreign relations of the Netherlands">Dutch foreign policy</a> has been characterised by its <a href="/wiki/Neutral_state" class="mw-redirect" title="Neutral state">neutrality</a>. Since World War II, the Netherlands has become a member of a large number of international organisations, most prominently the UN, <a href="/wiki/NATO" title="NATO">NATO</a> and the EU. The Dutch economy is very open and relies strongly on <a href="/wiki/International_trade" title="International trade">international trade</a>. </p>
      <p>The <a href="/wiki/Foreign_policy" title="Foreign policy">foreign policy</a> of the Netherlands is based on four basic commitments: to <a href="/wiki/Atlanticism" title="Atlanticism">Atlantic co-operation</a>, to <a href="/wiki/European_integration" title="European integration">European integration</a>, to <a href="/wiki/International_development" title="International development">international development</a> and to <a href="/wiki/International_law" title="International law">international law</a>. One of the more controversial international issues surrounding the Netherlands is its <a href="/wiki/Drug_policy_of_the_Netherlands" title="Drug policy of the Netherlands">liberal policy towards soft drugs</a>. </p>
      <p>During and after the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Golden_Age" title="Dutch Golden Age">Dutch Golden Age</a>, the Dutch people built up a commercial and colonial empire. The most important colonies were present-day <a href="/wiki/Suriname" title="Suriname">Suriname</a> and <a href="/wiki/Indonesia" title="Indonesia">Indonesia</a>. Indonesia became independent after the <a href="/wiki/Indonesian_National_Revolution" title="Indonesian National Revolution">Indonesian National Revolution</a> in the 1940s following a war of independence, international pressure and several <a href="/wiki/United_Nations_Security_Council_resolution" title="United Nations Security Council resolution">United Nations Security Council resolutions</a>. Suriname became independent in 1975. The historical ties inherited from its colonial past still influence the foreign relations of the Netherlands. In addition, many people from these countries are living permanently in the Netherlands. </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Military">Military</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=29" title="Edit section: Military">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/Armed_forces_of_the_Netherlands" title="Armed forces of the Netherlands">Armed forces of the Netherlands</a>
      </div> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Rob_Bauer.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Rob_Bauer.jpg/220px-Rob_Bauer.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Rob_Bauer.jpg/330px-Rob_Bauer.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Rob_Bauer.jpg/440px-Rob_Bauer.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3321" data-file-height="2214"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Rob_Bauer.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Lieutenant admiral <a href="/wiki/Rob_Bauer" title="Rob Bauer">Rob Bauer</a> is the current <a href="/wiki/Chief_of_Defence_(Netherlands)" title="Chief of Defence (Netherlands)">Chief of Defence</a>.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The Netherlands has one of the oldest standing armies in Europe; it was first established as such by <a href="/wiki/Maurice_of_Nassau" class="mw-redirect" title="Maurice of Nassau">Maurice of Nassau</a> in the late 1500s. The Dutch army was used throughout the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Empire" title="Dutch Empire">Dutch Empire</a>. After the defeat of Napoleon, the Dutch army was transformed into a <a href="/wiki/Conscription" title="Conscription">conscription</a> army. The army was unsuccessfully deployed during the <a href="/wiki/Belgian_Revolution" title="Belgian Revolution">Belgian Revolution</a> in 1830. After 1830, it was deployed mainly in the Dutch colonies, as the Netherlands remained neutral in European wars (including the First World War), until the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_the_Netherlands" title="Battle of the Netherlands">Netherlands was invaded in World War II</a> and defeated by the Wehrmacht in May 1940. </p> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:HNLMS_Holland.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/HNLMS_Holland.jpg/220px-HNLMS_Holland.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/HNLMS_Holland.jpg/330px-HNLMS_Holland.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/HNLMS_Holland.jpg/440px-HNLMS_Holland.jpg 2x" data-file-width="960" data-file-height="640"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:HNLMS_Holland.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div><i>Zr. Ms. Holland</i>, a <a href="/wiki/Royal_Netherlands_Navy" title="Royal Netherlands Navy">Royal Netherlands Navy</a> <a href="/wiki/Offshore_patrol_vessel" class="mw-redirect" title="Offshore patrol vessel">offshore patrol vessel</a>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The Netherlands abandoned its neutrality in 1948 when it signed the <a href="/wiki/Treaty_of_Brussels" title="Treaty of Brussels">Treaty of Brussels</a>, and became a founding member of <a href="/wiki/NATO" title="NATO">NATO</a> in 1949. The Dutch military was therefore part of the NATO strength in <a href="/wiki/Cold_War" title="Cold War">Cold War</a> Europe, deploying its army to several bases in Germany. More than 3,000 Dutch soldiers were assigned to the <a href="/wiki/2nd_Infantry_Division_(United_States)" title="2nd Infantry Division (United States)">2nd Infantry Division</a> of the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Army" title="United States Army">United States Army</a> during the <a href="/wiki/Korean_War" title="Korean War">Korean War</a>. In 1996 conscription was suspended, and the Dutch army was once again transformed into a professional army. Since the 1990s the Dutch army has been involved in the <a href="/wiki/Bosnian_War" title="Bosnian War">Bosnian War</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Kosovo_War" title="Kosovo War">Kosovo War</a>, it held a province in <a href="/wiki/Iraq" title="Iraq">Iraq</a> after the defeat of <a href="/wiki/Saddam_Hussein" title="Saddam Hussein">Saddam Hussein</a>, and it was engaged in <a href="/wiki/War_in_Afghanistan_(2001%E2%80%93present)" title="War in Afghanistan (2001–present)">Afghanistan</a>. </p>
      <p>The military is composed of four branches, all of which carry the prefix <i>Koninklijke</i> (Royal): </p> 
      <ul>
       <li><i>Koninklijke Marine</i> (KM), the <a href="/wiki/Royal_Netherlands_Navy" title="Royal Netherlands Navy">Royal Netherlands Navy</a>, including the Naval Air Service and Marine Corps;</li> 
       <li><i>Koninklijke Landmacht</i> (KL), the <a href="/wiki/Royal_Netherlands_Army" title="Royal Netherlands Army">Royal Netherlands Army</a>;</li> 
       <li><i>Koninklijke Luchtmacht</i> (KLu), the <a href="/wiki/Royal_Netherlands_Air_Force" title="Royal Netherlands Air Force">Royal Netherlands Air Force</a>;</li> 
       <li><i>Koninklijke Marechaussee</i> (KMar), the <a href="/wiki/Royal_Marechaussee" title="Royal Marechaussee">Royal Marechaussee</a> (Military Police), tasks include military police and border control.</li>
      </ul> 
      <p>The submarine service is open to women as of 1 January 2017. The <a href="/wiki/Korps_Commandotroepen" title="Korps Commandotroepen">Korps Commandotroepen</a>, the Special Operations Force of the Netherlands Army, is open to women, but because of the extremely high physical demands for initial training, it is almost impossible for a woman to become a commando.<sup id="cite_ref-147" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-147">[138]</a></sup> The Dutch Ministry of Defence employs more than 70,000 personnel, including over 20,000 civilians and over 50,000 military personnel.<sup id="cite_ref-148" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-148">[139]</a></sup> In April 2011 the government announced a major reduction in its military because of a cut in government expenditure, including a decrease in the number of tanks, fighter aircraft, naval ships and senior officials.<sup id="cite_ref-149" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-149">[140]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The Netherlands has ratified many international conventions concerning <a href="/wiki/International_humanitarian_law" title="International humanitarian law">war law</a>. The Netherlands decided not to sign the UN <a href="/wiki/Treaty_on_the_Prohibition_of_Nuclear_Weapons" title="Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons">treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-150" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-150">[141]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Economy">Economy</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=30" title="Edit section: Economy">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/Economy_of_the_Netherlands" title="Economy of the Netherlands">Economy of the Netherlands</a>
      </div> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Smile_29Aug07_5,_at_the_Amazone_harbour,_Port_of_Rotterdam,_Holland_29-Aug-2007.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Smile_29Aug07_5%2C_at_the_Amazone_harbour%2C_Port_of_Rotterdam%2C_Holland_29-Aug-2007.jpg/220px-Smile_29Aug07_5%2C_at_the_Amazone_harbour%2C_Port_of_Rotterdam%2C_Holland_29-Aug-2007.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Smile_29Aug07_5%2C_at_the_Amazone_harbour%2C_Port_of_Rotterdam%2C_Holland_29-Aug-2007.jpg/330px-Smile_29Aug07_5%2C_at_the_Amazone_harbour%2C_Port_of_Rotterdam%2C_Holland_29-Aug-2007.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Smile_29Aug07_5%2C_at_the_Amazone_harbour%2C_Port_of_Rotterdam%2C_Holland_29-Aug-2007.jpg/440px-Smile_29Aug07_5%2C_at_the_Amazone_harbour%2C_Port_of_Rotterdam%2C_Holland_29-Aug-2007.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3488" data-file-height="2616"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Smile_29Aug07_5,_at_the_Amazone_harbour,_Port_of_Rotterdam,_Holland_29-Aug-2007.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>The <a href="/wiki/Port_of_Rotterdam" title="Port of Rotterdam">Port of Rotterdam</a> is Europe's largest port.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The Netherlands has a developed economy and has been playing a special role in the European economy for many centuries. Since the 16th century, shipping, fishing, agriculture, trade, and banking have been leading sectors of the Dutch economy. The Netherlands has <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_economic_freedom" title="List of countries by economic freedom">a high level of economic freedom</a>. The Netherlands is one of the top countries in the <a href="/wiki/Global_Enabling_Trade_Report" title="Global Enabling Trade Report">Global Enabling Trade Report</a> (2nd in 2016), and was ranked the fifth most competitive economy in the world by the Swiss <a href="/wiki/International_Institute_for_Management_Development" title="International Institute for Management Development">International Institute for Management Development</a> in 2017.<sup id="cite_ref-151" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-151">[142]</a></sup> In addition, the country was ranked the second most innovative nation in the world in the 2018 <a href="/wiki/Global_Innovation_Index" title="Global Innovation Index">Global Innovation Index</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-152" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-152">[143]</a></sup> </p> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Netherlands.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Netherlands.jpg/220px-Netherlands.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="166" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Netherlands.jpg/330px-Netherlands.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Netherlands.jpg/440px-Netherlands.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2544" data-file-height="1920"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Netherlands.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>The Netherlands is a heavily developed country. Shown here is a motorway passing by a <a href="/wiki/Polder" title="Polder">polder</a> with a <a href="/wiki/Windpump" title="Windpump">drainage windmill</a>, and two <a href="/wiki/Wind_turbines" class="mw-redirect" title="Wind turbines">wind turbines</a> in the background.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>As of 2020<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, the key trading partners of the Netherlands were Germany, Belgium, the United Kingdom, the United States, France, Italy, China and Russia.<sup id="cite_ref-153" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-153">[144]</a></sup> The Netherlands is one of the world's 10 leading exporting countries. Foodstuffs form the largest industrial sector. Other major industries include chemicals, metallurgy, machinery, electrical goods, trade, services and tourism. Examples of international Dutch companies operating in Netherlands include <a href="/wiki/Randstad_Holding" title="Randstad Holding">Randstad</a>, <a href="/wiki/Unilever" title="Unilever">Unilever</a>, <a href="/wiki/Heineken_International" class="mw-redirect" title="Heineken International">Heineken</a>, <a href="/wiki/KLM" title="KLM">KLM</a>, financial services (<a href="/wiki/ING_Group" title="ING Group">ING</a>, <a href="/wiki/ABN_AMRO" title="ABN AMRO">ABN AMRO</a>, <a href="/wiki/Rabobank" title="Rabobank">Rabobank</a>), chemicals (<a href="/wiki/DSM_(company)" title="DSM (company)">DSM</a>, <a href="/wiki/AkzoNobel" title="AkzoNobel">AKZO</a>), petroleum refining (<a href="/wiki/Royal_Dutch_Shell" title="Royal Dutch Shell">Royal Dutch Shell</a>), electronical machinery (<a href="/wiki/Philips" title="Philips">Philips</a>, <a href="/wiki/ASML_Holding" title="ASML Holding">ASML</a>), and satellite navigation (<a href="/wiki/TomTom" title="TomTom">TomTom</a>). </p>
      <p>The Netherlands has the <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(nominal)" title="List of countries by GDP (nominal)">17th-largest economy in the world</a>, and <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(nominal)_per_capita" title="List of countries by GDP (nominal) per capita">ranks 11th in GDP (nominal) per capita</a>. Between 1997 and 2000 annual economic growth (GDP) averaged nearly 4%, well above the European average. Growth slowed considerably from 2001 to 2005 with the global economic slowdown, but accelerated to 4.1% in the third quarter of 2007. In May 2013, inflation was at 2.8% per year.<sup id="cite_ref-154" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-154">[145]</a></sup> In April 2013, unemployment was at 8.2% (or 6.7% following the <a href="/wiki/International_Labour_Organization" title="International Labour Organization">ILO</a> definition) of the <a href="/wiki/Labour_force" class="mw-redirect" title="Labour force">labour force</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-155" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-155">[146]</a></sup> In February 2019, this was reduced to 3.4%.<sup id="cite_ref-156" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-156">[147]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>In Q3 and Q4 2011, the Dutch economy contracted by 0.4% and 0.7%, respectively, because of European Debt Crisis, while in Q4 the Eurozone economy shrunk by 0.3%.<sup id="cite_ref-157" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-157">[148]</a></sup> The Netherlands also has a relatively low <a href="/wiki/Gini_coefficient" title="Gini coefficient">GINI coefficient</a> of 0.326. Despite ranking 11th in <a href="/wiki/GDP_per_capita" class="mw-redirect" title="GDP per capita">GDP per capita</a>, <a href="/wiki/UNICEF" title="UNICEF">UNICEF</a> ranked the Netherlands 1st in child well-being in rich countries, both in 2007 and in 2013.<sup id="cite_ref-158" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-158">[149]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-159" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-159">[150]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-160" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-160">[151]</a></sup> On the <a href="/wiki/Index_of_Economic_Freedom" title="Index of Economic Freedom">Index of Economic Freedom</a> Netherlands is the 14th most <a href="/wiki/Free_market" title="Free market">free market</a> capitalist economy out of 180 surveyed countries. </p>
      <p><a href="/wiki/Amsterdam" title="Amsterdam">Amsterdam</a> is the financial and business capital of the Netherlands.<sup id="cite_ref-ez_161-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ez-161">[152]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Amsterdam_Stock_Exchange" class="mw-redirect" title="Amsterdam Stock Exchange">Amsterdam Stock Exchange</a> (AEX), part of <a href="/wiki/Euronext" title="Euronext">Euronext</a>, is the world's oldest stock exchange and is one of Europe's largest bourses. It is situated near <a href="/wiki/Dam_Square" title="Dam Square">Dam Square</a> in the city's centre. As a founding member of the <a href="/wiki/Euro" title="Euro">euro</a>, the Netherlands replaced (for accounting purposes) its former currency, the "gulden" (<a href="/wiki/Dutch_guilder" title="Dutch guilder">guilder</a>), on 1 January 1999, along with 15 other adopters of the euro. Actual <a href="/wiki/Euro_coins" title="Euro coins">euro coins</a> and <a href="/wiki/Euro_banknotes" title="Euro banknotes">banknotes</a> followed on 1 January 2002. One euro was equivalent to 2.20371 Dutch guilders. In the <a href="/wiki/Caribbean_Netherlands" title="Caribbean Netherlands">Caribbean Netherlands</a>, the <a href="/wiki/United_States_dollar" title="United States dollar">United States dollar</a> is used instead of the euro. </p> 
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:BlueEurozone.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/BlueEurozone.svg/220px-BlueEurozone.svg.png" decoding="async" width="220" height="235" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/BlueEurozone.svg/330px-BlueEurozone.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/BlueEurozone.svg/440px-BlueEurozone.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="645" data-file-height="690"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:BlueEurozone.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>The Netherlands is part of a monetary union, the <a href="/wiki/Eurozone" title="Eurozone">Eurozone</a> (dark blue), and the <a href="/wiki/Internal_Market_(European_Union)" class="mw-redirect" title="Internal Market (European Union)">EU single market</a>.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The Dutch location gives it prime access to markets in the UK and Germany, with the <a href="/wiki/Port_of_Rotterdam" title="Port of Rotterdam">Port of Rotterdam</a> being the largest port in Europe. Other important parts of the economy are <a href="/wiki/International_trade" title="International trade">international trade</a> (Dutch colonialism started with co-operative private enterprises such as the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_East_India_Company" title="Dutch East India Company">Dutch East India Company</a>), banking and transport. The Netherlands successfully addressed the issue of public finances and stagnating job growth long before its European partners. Amsterdam is the 5th-busiest tourist destination in Europe with more than 4.2&nbsp;million international visitors.<sup id="cite_ref-42milvisitors_162-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42milvisitors-162">[153]</a></sup> Since the enlargement of the EU large numbers of <a href="/wiki/Migrant_worker" title="Migrant worker">migrant workers</a> have arrived in the Netherlands from <a href="/wiki/Central_Europe" title="Central Europe">Central</a> and <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Europe" title="Eastern Europe">Eastern Europe</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-163" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-163">[154]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The Netherlands continues to be one of the leading European nations for attracting foreign direct investment and is one of the five largest investors in the United States. The economy experienced a slowdown in 2005, but in 2006 recovered to the fastest pace in six years on the back of increased exports and strong investment. The pace of job growth reached 10-year highs in 2007. The Netherlands is the fourth-most competitive economy in the world, according to the <a href="/wiki/World_Economic_Forum" title="World Economic Forum">World Economic Forum</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Global_Competitiveness_Report" title="Global Competitiveness Report">Global Competitiveness Report</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-wefcomp_164-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wefcomp-164">[155]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Natural_gas">Natural gas</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=31" title="Edit section: Natural gas">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Natural_gas_NL.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Natural_gas_NL.png/250px-Natural_gas_NL.png" decoding="async" width="250" height="235" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Natural_gas_NL.png/375px-Natural_gas_NL.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Natural_gas_NL.png/500px-Natural_gas_NL.png 2x" data-file-width="1100" data-file-height="1032"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Natural_gas_NL.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Natural gas concessions in the Netherlands. Today the Netherlands accounts for more than 25% of all natural gas reserves in the EU.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>Beginning in the 1950s, the Netherlands discovered huge natural gas resources. The sale of natural gas generated enormous revenues for the Netherlands for decades, adding hundreds of billions of euros to the government's budget.<sup id="cite_ref-vorige.nrc.nl_165-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-vorige.nrc.nl-165">[156]</a></sup> However, the unforeseen consequences of the country's huge energy wealth impacted the competitiveness of other sectors of the economy, leading to the theory of <a href="/wiki/Dutch_disease" title="Dutch disease">Dutch disease</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-vorige.nrc.nl_165-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-vorige.nrc.nl-165">[156]</a></sup> </p> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Wildervank_natural_gas_field.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Wildervank_natural_gas_field.jpg/250px-Wildervank_natural_gas_field.jpg" decoding="async" width="250" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Wildervank_natural_gas_field.jpg/375px-Wildervank_natural_gas_field.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Wildervank_natural_gas_field.jpg/500px-Wildervank_natural_gas_field.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4937" data-file-height="3262"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Wildervank_natural_gas_field.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>The <a href="/wiki/Groningen_gas_field" title="Groningen gas field">Groningen gas field</a> whose discovery in 1959 transformed the Dutch economy, generating €159 billion in revenue since the mid-1970s.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>Apart from coal and gas, the country has no mining resources. The last coal mine was closed in 1974. The <a href="/wiki/Groningen_gas_field" title="Groningen gas field">Groningen gas field</a>, one of the largest <a href="/wiki/Natural-gas_field" class="mw-redirect" title="Natural-gas field">natural-gas fields</a> in the world, is situated near <a href="/wiki/Slochteren" title="Slochteren">Slochteren</a>. Exploitation of this field has resulted in €159&nbsp;billion in revenue since the mid-1970s.<sup id="cite_ref-geo_166-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-geo-166">[157]</a></sup> The field is operated by government-owned Gasunie and output is jointly exploited by the government, Royal Dutch Shell, and Exxon Mobil through NAM (Nederlandse Aardolie Maatschappij). "Gas extraction has resulted in increasingly strong earth tremors, some measuring as much as 3.6 on the Richter magnitude scale. The cost of damage repairs, structural improvements to buildings, and compensation for home value decreases has been estimated at 6.5 billion euros. Around 35,000 homes are said to be affected."<sup id="cite_ref-167" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-167">[158]</a></sup> The Netherlands have an estimated 25% of natural gas reserves in the EU.<sup id="cite_ref-stp_168-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-stp-168">[159]</a></sup> The energy sector accounted for almost 11% of the GDP in 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-169" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-169">[160]</a></sup> Netherlands's economy, mainly due to the large shares of natural gas reserves, is considered to have "very high" <a href="/wiki/Energy_intensity" title="Energy intensity">energy intensity</a> rating.<sup id="cite_ref-170" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-170">[161]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Netherlands is faced with future challenges as the energy supply is forecasted to fall short of the demand by the year 2025 in the gas sector. This is attributed to the depletion of Netherlands's major gas field, Groningen, and the earthquakes that have hit the Groningen region.<sup id="cite_ref-171" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-171">[162]</a></sup> In addition, there is ambiguity surrounding the feasibility of producing unconventional gas. Netherlands relies heavily on natural gas to provide energy. Gas is the main source of heating for households in Netherlands<sup id="cite_ref-stp_168-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-stp-168">[159]</a></sup> and represented 35% of the energy mix in 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-bbs_172-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbs-172">[163]</a></sup> Furthermore, The <a href="/wiki/European_Union_climate_and_energy_package" title="European Union climate and energy package">European Union 2020 package</a> (20% reduction in GHG emissions, 20% renewables in the energy mix and 20% improvement in energy efficiency) enacted in 2009 has influenced the domestic energy politics of Netherlands and pressured non-state actors to give consent to more aggressive energy reforms that would reduce reliance on natural resources as a source of income to the economy.<sup id="cite_ref-yea_173-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-yea-173">[164]</a></sup> Therefore, a transition towards renewable energy has been a key objective by Netherlands in order to safeguard the energy security of the country from natural resources depletion, mainly gas.<sup id="cite_ref-stp_168-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-stp-168">[159]</a></sup> Netherlands has set a 14% renewable energy target of the total energy mix by the year 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-neo_174-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-neo-174">[165]</a></sup> However, the continuation of providing tax breaks to electricity generated by coal and gas, and to the exploration and extraction of gas from fields that are "insufficiently" profitable,<sup id="cite_ref-EuropeanEnvironmentalAgency_175-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EuropeanEnvironmentalAgency-175">[166]</a></sup> renders a successful transition towards renewable energy more difficult to achieve due to inconsistencies in the policy mix. In 2011, it was estimated that the renewable energy sector received 31% (EUR 743MM), while the conventional energy sector received 69% (EUR 1.6B), of the total <a href="/wiki/Energy_subsidies" class="mw-redirect" title="Energy subsidies">energy subsidies</a> by the government.<sup id="cite_ref-EuropeanEnvironmentalAgency_175-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EuropeanEnvironmentalAgency-175">[166]</a></sup> Furthermore, the energy market in Netherlands remains to be dominated by few major corporations Nuon, RWE, E.ON, Eneco and Delta that have significant influence over the energy policy.<sup id="cite_ref-deloitte_176-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-deloitte-176">[167]</a></sup> Renewable energy share in the energy mix is estimated to reach 12.4% by the year 2020, falling 1.6% short of the 14% target.<sup id="cite_ref-neo_174-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-neo-174">[165]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Agriculture_and_natural_resources">Agriculture and natural resources</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=32" title="Edit section: Agriculture and natural resources">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Dutch_belted_cows_at_Park_Sonsbeek_meadows_in_the_centre_of_the_city_of_Arnhem_(look_the_background)_-_panoramio.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Dutch_belted_cows_at_Park_Sonsbeek_meadows_in_the_centre_of_the_city_of_Arnhem_%28look_the_background%29_-_panoramio.jpg/220px-Dutch_belted_cows_at_Park_Sonsbeek_meadows_in_the_centre_of_the_city_of_Arnhem_%28look_the_background%29_-_panoramio.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Dutch_belted_cows_at_Park_Sonsbeek_meadows_in_the_centre_of_the_city_of_Arnhem_%28look_the_background%29_-_panoramio.jpg/330px-Dutch_belted_cows_at_Park_Sonsbeek_meadows_in_the_centre_of_the_city_of_Arnhem_%28look_the_background%29_-_panoramio.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Dutch_belted_cows_at_Park_Sonsbeek_meadows_in_the_centre_of_the_city_of_Arnhem_%28look_the_background%29_-_panoramio.jpg/440px-Dutch_belted_cows_at_Park_Sonsbeek_meadows_in_the_centre_of_the_city_of_Arnhem_%28look_the_background%29_-_panoramio.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3000" data-file-height="2000"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Dutch_belted_cows_at_Park_Sonsbeek_meadows_in_the_centre_of_the_city_of_Arnhem_(look_the_background)_-_panoramio.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Cows near the city of <a href="/wiki/Arnhem" title="Arnhem">Arnhem</a>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>From a biological resource perspective, the Netherlands has a low endowment: the Netherlands’ <a href="/wiki/Biocapacity" title="Biocapacity">biocapacity</a> adds up to only 0.8 global hectares in 2016, 0.2 of which are dedicated to agriculture.<sup id="cite_ref-footprintdata_177-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-footprintdata-177">[168]</a></sup> The Dutch biocapacity per person is just about half of the 1.6 global hectares of biocapacity per person available worldwide.<sup id="cite_ref-178" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-178">[169]</a></sup> In contrast, in 2016, the Dutch used on average 4.8 global hectares of biocapacity - their <a href="/wiki/Ecological_footprint" title="Ecological footprint">ecological footprint</a> of consumption. This means the Dutch required nearly six times as much biocapacity as the Netherlands contains. As a result, the Netherlands was running a biocapacity deficit of 4.0 global hectares per person in 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-footprintdata_177-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-footprintdata-177">[168]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The Dutch agricultural sector is highly mechanised, and has a strong focus on international exports. It employs about 4% of the Dutch labour force but produces large surpluses in the food-processing industry and accounts for 21 percent of the Dutch total export value.<sup id="cite_ref-179" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-179">[170]</a></sup> The Dutch rank first in the European Union and second worldwide in value of agricultural exports, behind only the United States,<sup id="cite_ref-180" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-180">[171]</a></sup> with agricultural exports earning €80.7&nbsp;billion in 2014,<sup id="cite_ref-government.nl_181-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-government.nl-181">[172]</a></sup> up from €75.4&nbsp;billion in 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-hollandtrade.com_33-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hollandtrade.com-33">[25]</a></sup> In 2019 agricultural exports were worth €94.5 billion.<sup id="cite_ref-182" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-182">[173]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>One-third of the world's exports of <a href="/wiki/Capsicum" title="Capsicum">chilis</a>, tomatoes and cucumbers goes through the country. The Netherlands also exports one-fifteenth of the world's apples.<sup id="cite_ref-USDA_Foreign_Agriculture_Service_183-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-USDA_Foreign_Agriculture_Service-183">[174]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Aside from that, a significant portion of Dutch agricultural exports consists of fresh-cut plants, flowers, and flower bulbs, with the Netherlands exporting two-thirds of the world's total.<sup id="cite_ref-USDA_Foreign_Agriculture_Service_183-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-USDA_Foreign_Agriculture_Service-183">[174]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Demographics">Demographics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=33" title="Edit section: Demographics">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/Demography_of_the_Netherlands" title="Demography of the Netherlands">Demography of the Netherlands</a>
      </div> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Population_of_the_Netherlands_1900-2000.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/2/2c/Population_of_the_Netherlands_1900-2000.png/220px-Population_of_the_Netherlands_1900-2000.png" decoding="async" width="220" height="166" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/2/2c/Population_of_the_Netherlands_1900-2000.png/330px-Population_of_the_Netherlands_1900-2000.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/2/2c/Population_of_the_Netherlands_1900-2000.png 2x" data-file-width="416" data-file-height="313"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Population_of_the_Netherlands_1900-2000.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Population of the Netherlands from 1900 to 2000
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The Netherlands had an estimated population of 17,474,677 as of 31 December 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-auto_10-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-auto-10">[7]</a></sup> It is the <a href="/wiki/Area_and_population_of_European_countries" title="Area and population of European countries">5th most densely populated</a> country in <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a>, and except for the very small <a href="/wiki/City-states" class="mw-redirect" title="City-states">city-states</a> like <a href="/wiki/Monaco" title="Monaco">Monaco</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vatican_City" title="Vatican City">Vatican City</a> and <a href="/wiki/San_Marino" title="San Marino">San Marino</a> it is the most densely populated country in Europe. And it is the <a href="/wiki/List_of_sovereign_states_and_dependent_territories_by_population_density" class="mw-redirect" title="List of sovereign states and dependent territories by population density">16th most densely populated</a> country in the world with a density of 424 per square kilometre (1,100/sq&nbsp;mi). It is the <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_population" class="mw-redirect" title="List of countries by population">67th most populous country</a> in the world. Between 1900 and 1950, the country's population almost doubled from 5.1 to 10 million. From 1950 to 2000, the population further increased, to 15.9&nbsp;million, though this represented a lower rate of <a href="/wiki/Population_growth" title="Population growth">population growth</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-184" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-184">[175]</a></sup> The estimated growth rate in 2013<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup> is 0.44%.<sup id="cite_ref-cia-worldfactbook-nl_185-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cia-worldfactbook-nl-185">[176]</a></sup> </p> 
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Netherlandspop.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Netherlandspop.svg/220px-Netherlandspop.svg.png" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Netherlandspop.svg/330px-Netherlandspop.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Netherlandspop.svg/440px-Netherlandspop.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="600"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Netherlandspop.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div><a href="/wiki/Population_pyramid" title="Population pyramid">Population pyramid</a> of the Netherlands in 2017
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The <a href="/wiki/Fertility_rate" class="mw-redirect" title="Fertility rate">fertility rate</a> in the Netherlands is 1.78 children per woman (2018 estimate),<sup id="cite_ref-cia-worldfactbook-nl_185-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cia-worldfactbook-nl-185">[176]</a></sup> which is high compared with many other European countries, but <a href="/wiki/Sub-replacement_fertility" title="Sub-replacement fertility">below the rate of 2.1 children per woman required for natural population replacement</a>, it remains considerably below the high of 5.39 children born per woman in 1879.<sup id="cite_ref-186" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-186">[177]</a></sup> Netherlands subsequently has one of the oldest populations in the world, with the average age of 42.7 years.<sup id="cite_ref-cia-worldfactbook-nl_185-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cia-worldfactbook-nl-185">[176]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Life_expectancy" title="Life expectancy">Life expectancy</a> is high in the Netherlands: 84.3 years for newborn girls and 79.7 for boys (2020 estimate).<sup id="cite_ref-cia-worldfactbook-nl_185-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cia-worldfactbook-nl-185">[176]</a></sup> The country has a <a href="/wiki/Human_migration" title="Human migration">migration</a> rate of 1.9 migrants per 1,000 inhabitants per year.<sup id="cite_ref-cia-worldfactbook-nl_185-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cia-worldfactbook-nl-185">[176]</a></sup> The majority of the population of the Netherlands is ethnically <a href="/wiki/Dutch_people" title="Dutch people">Dutch</a>. According to a 2005 estimate, the population was 80.9% Dutch, 2.4% <a href="/wiki/Indonesia" title="Indonesia">Indonesian</a>, 2.4% <a href="/wiki/Germans" title="Germans">German</a>, 2.2% <a href="/wiki/Turkish-Dutch" class="mw-redirect" title="Turkish-Dutch">Turkish</a>, 2.0% <a href="/wiki/Surinamese_people" title="Surinamese people">Surinamese</a>, 1.9% <a href="/wiki/Morocco" title="Morocco">Moroccan</a>, 0.8% <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_Antilles" title="Netherlands Antilles">Antillean</a> and <a href="/wiki/Aruba" title="Aruba">Aruban</a>, and 7.4% others.<sup id="cite_ref-187" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-187">[178]</a></sup> Some 150,000 to 200,000 people living in the Netherlands are <a href="/wiki/Expatriate" title="Expatriate">expatriates</a>, mostly concentrated in and around <a href="/wiki/Amsterdam" title="Amsterdam">Amsterdam</a> and <a href="/wiki/The_Hague" title="The Hague">The Hague</a>, now constituting almost 10% of the population of these cities.<sup id="cite_ref-188" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-188">[179]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-189" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-189">[180]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The Dutch are the tallest people in the world, by nationality,<sup id="cite_ref-Science_2015-04-07_190-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Science_2015-04-07-190">[181]</a></sup> with an average height of 1.81 metres (5&nbsp;ft 11.3&nbsp;in) for adult males and 1.67 metres (5&nbsp;ft 5.7&nbsp;in) for adult females in 2009.<sup id="cite_ref-191" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-191">[182]</a></sup> People in the south are on average about 2&nbsp;cm (0.8 inches) shorter than those in the north. </p> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Grote_drukte_zomercarnaval_Rotterdam.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Grote_drukte_zomercarnaval_Rotterdam.jpg/220px-Grote_drukte_zomercarnaval_Rotterdam.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Grote_drukte_zomercarnaval_Rotterdam.jpg/330px-Grote_drukte_zomercarnaval_Rotterdam.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Grote_drukte_zomercarnaval_Rotterdam.jpg/440px-Grote_drukte_zomercarnaval_Rotterdam.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4090" data-file-height="2727"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Grote_drukte_zomercarnaval_Rotterdam.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>In <a href="/wiki/Rotterdam" title="Rotterdam">Rotterdam</a> almost half the population has an immigrant background.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>According to <a href="/wiki/Eurostat" title="Eurostat">Eurostat</a>, in 2010 there were 1.8 million <a href="/wiki/Foreign_born" title="Foreign born">foreign-born residents</a> in the Netherlands, corresponding to 11.1% of the total population. Of these, 1.4 million (8.5%) were born outside the EU and 0.43 million (2.6%) were born in another EU Member State.<sup id="cite_ref-192" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-192">[183]</a></sup> On 21 November 2016, there were 3.8 million residents in the Netherlands with at least one foreign-born parent ("migration background").<sup id="cite_ref-193" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-193">[184]</a></sup> Over half the young people in Amsterdam and Rotterdam have a non-western background.<sup id="cite_ref-194" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-194">[185]</a></sup> Dutch people, or <a href="/wiki/Dutch_diaspora" title="Dutch diaspora">descendants of Dutch people</a>, are also found in migrant communities worldwide, notably in <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canada</a>, <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">Australia</a>, <a href="/wiki/South_Africa" title="South Africa">South Africa</a> and the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. According to the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Census_Bureau" title="United States Census Bureau">United States Census Bureau</a> (2006), more than 5&nbsp;million Americans claim total or partial <a href="/wiki/Dutch_American" class="mw-redirect" title="Dutch American">Dutch</a> ancestry.<sup id="cite_ref-195" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-195">[186]</a></sup> There are close to 3&nbsp;million Dutch-descended <a href="/wiki/Afrikaner" class="mw-redirect" title="Afrikaner">Afrikaners</a> living in South Africa.<sup id="cite_ref-196" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-196">[187]</a></sup> In 1940, there were 290,000 Europeans and Eurasians in Indonesia,<sup id="cite_ref-197" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-197">[188]</a></sup> but most have since left the country.<sup id="cite_ref-198" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-198">[189]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The <a href="/wiki/Randstad" title="Randstad">Randstad</a> is the country's largest <a href="/wiki/Conurbation" title="Conurbation">conurbation</a> located in the west of the country and contains the four largest cities: <a href="/wiki/Amsterdam" title="Amsterdam">Amsterdam</a> in the province <a href="/wiki/North_Holland" title="North Holland">North Holland</a>, <a href="/wiki/Rotterdam" title="Rotterdam">Rotterdam</a> and <a href="/wiki/The_Hague" title="The Hague">The Hague</a> in the province <a href="/wiki/South_Holland" title="South Holland">South Holland</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Utrecht_(city)" class="mw-redirect" title="Utrecht (city)">Utrecht</a> in the province <a href="/wiki/Utrecht_(province)" title="Utrecht (province)">Utrecht</a>. The Randstad has a population of about 8.2&nbsp;million inhabitants<sup id="cite_ref-199" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-199">[190]</a></sup> and is the <a href="/wiki/List_of_metropolitan_areas_in_Europe_by_population" class="mw-redirect" title="List of metropolitan areas in Europe by population">5th largest</a> <a href="/wiki/Metropolitan_area" title="Metropolitan area">metropolitan area</a> in Europe. According to Dutch Central Statistics Bureau, in 2015, 28 percent of the Dutch population had a spendable income above 45,000 euros (which does not include spending on health care or education).<sup id="cite_ref-200" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-200">[191]</a></sup> </p>
      <p><br> </p>

      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Functional_urban_areas">Functional urban areas</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=34" title="Edit section: Functional urban areas">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:352px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Population_density_in_the_Netherlands.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Population_density_in_the_Netherlands.png/350px-Population_density_in_the_Netherlands.png" decoding="async" width="350" height="453" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Population_density_in_the_Netherlands.png/525px-Population_density_in_the_Netherlands.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/18/Population_density_in_the_Netherlands.png 2x" data-file-width="575" data-file-height="745"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Population_density_in_the_Netherlands.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Population density in the Netherlands by <a href="/wiki/Municipalities_of_the_Netherlands" title="Municipalities of the Netherlands">municipality</a>. The largest urban area, the <a href="/wiki/Randstad" title="Randstad">Randstad</a> is clearly visible along the west coast.
        </div>
