           <a href="/wiki/Water_Mill_at_Kollen_Near_Nuenen" title="Water Mill at Kollen Near Nuenen">Water Mill at Kollen Near Nuenen</a> by Brabantine artist <a href="/wiki/Vincent_van_Gogh" title="Vincent van Gogh">Vincent van Gogh</a>
          </div>
         </div>
        </div>
        <div class="trow">
         <div class="tsingle" style="width:290px;max-width:290px">
          <div class="thumbimage" style="height:161px;overflow:hidden">
           <a href="/wiki/File:Rijksmuseum_2022.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Rijksmuseum_2022.jpg/288px-Rijksmuseum_2022.jpg" decoding="async" width="288" height="162" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Rijksmuseum_2022.jpg/432px-Rijksmuseum_2022.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Rijksmuseum_2022.jpg/576px-Rijksmuseum_2022.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4582" data-file-height="2577"></a>
          </div>
          <div class="thumbcaption text-align-center">
           The <a href="/wiki/Rijksmuseum" title="Rijksmuseum">Rijksmuseum</a> in Amsterdam
          </div>
         </div>
        </div>
        <div class="trow">
         <div class="tsingle" style="width:290px;max-width:290px">
          <div class="thumbimage" style="height:214px;overflow:hidden">
           <a href="/wiki/File:Gevel_Escher_in_Het_Paleis_300_dpi.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Gevel_Escher_in_Het_Paleis_300_dpi.jpg/288px-Gevel_Escher_in_Het_Paleis_300_dpi.jpg" decoding="async" width="288" height="214" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Gevel_Escher_in_Het_Paleis_300_dpi.jpg/432px-Gevel_Escher_in_Het_Paleis_300_dpi.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Gevel_Escher_in_Het_Paleis_300_dpi.jpg/576px-Gevel_Escher_in_Het_Paleis_300_dpi.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4590" data-file-height="3417"></a>
          </div>
         </div>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The Netherlands has had many well-known painters. In the Middle Ages <a href="/wiki/Hieronymus_Bosch" title="Hieronymus Bosch">Hieronymus Bosch</a>, <a href="/wiki/Petrus_Christus" title="Petrus Christus">Petrus Christus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lucas_Gassel" title="Lucas Gassel">Lucas Gassel</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pieter_Bruegel_the_Elder" title="Pieter Bruegel the Elder">Pieter Bruegel the Elder</a> were leading Dutch pioneers. </p>
      <p>During the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Golden_Age" title="Dutch Golden Age">Dutch Golden Age</a>, spanning much of the 17th century, the Dutch Republic was prosperous and witnessed a flourishing artistic movement. This was the age of the "Dutch Masters", such as <a href="/wiki/Rembrandt_Harmenszoon_van_Rijn" class="mw-redirect" title="Rembrandt Harmenszoon van Rijn">Rembrandt van Rijn</a>, <a href="/wiki/Johannes_Vermeer" title="Johannes Vermeer">Johannes Vermeer</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jan_Steen" title="Jan Steen">Jan Steen</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jacob_van_Ruisdael" title="Jacob van Ruisdael">Jacob van Ruisdael</a>, <a href="/wiki/Gerard_van_Honthorst" title="Gerard van Honthorst">Gerard van Honthorst</a>, <a href="/wiki/Theodoor_van_Thulden" title="Theodoor van Thulden">Theodoor van Thulden</a> and many others. </p>
      <p>Famous Dutch painters of the 19th and 20th century were <a href="/wiki/Vincent_van_Gogh" title="Vincent van Gogh">Vincent van Gogh</a> and the luminists <a href="/wiki/Jan_Sluijters" class="mw-redirect" title="Jan Sluijters">Jan Sluijters</a>, <a href="/wiki/Leo_Gestel" title="Leo Gestel">Leo Gestel</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Piet_Mondrian" title="Piet Mondrian">Piet Mondriaan</a>. <a href="/wiki/M._C._Escher" title="M. C. Escher">M. C. Escher</a> is a well-known graphics artist. <a href="/wiki/Willem_de_Kooning" title="Willem de Kooning">Willem de Kooning</a> was born and trained in <a href="/wiki/Rotterdam" title="Rotterdam">Rotterdam</a>, although he is considered to have reached acclaim as an American artist. </p>
      <p>Literature flourished as well during the Dutch Golden Age, with <a href="/wiki/Joost_van_den_Vondel" title="Joost van den Vondel">Joost van den Vondel</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pieter_Corneliszoon_Hooft" title="Pieter Corneliszoon Hooft">P. C. Hooft</a> as the two most famous writers. In the 19th century, <a href="/wiki/Multatuli" title="Multatuli">Multatuli</a> wrote about the poor treatment of the natives in the Dutch colony, the current Indonesia. Important 20th century authors include <a href="/wiki/Godfried_Bomans" title="Godfried Bomans">Godfried Bomans</a>, <a href="/wiki/Harry_Mulisch" title="Harry Mulisch">Harry Mulisch</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jan_Wolkers" title="Jan Wolkers">Jan Wolkers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Simon_Vestdijk" title="Simon Vestdijk">Simon Vestdijk</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hella_S._Haasse" class="mw-redirect" title="Hella S. Haasse">Hella S. Haasse</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cees_Nooteboom" title="Cees Nooteboom">Cees Nooteboom</a>, <a href="/wiki/Gerard_Reve" title="Gerard Reve">Gerard Reve</a> and <a href="/wiki/Willem_Frederik_Hermans" title="Willem Frederik Hermans">Willem Frederik Hermans</a>. <a href="/wiki/Anne_Frank" title="Anne Frank">Anne Frank</a>'s <a href="/wiki/The_Diary_of_a_Young_Girl" title="The Diary of a Young Girl"><i>Diary of a Young Girl</i></a> was published after she was murdered in the Holocaust and translated from Dutch to all major languages. </p>
      <p>Various architectural styles can be distinguished in the Netherlands. Over the years, various styles have been built and preserved. </p>
      <p>The <a href="/wiki/Romanesque_architecture" title="Romanesque architecture">Romanesque architecture</a> was built between the years 950 and 1250. This architectural style is most concentrated in the provinces of <a href="/wiki/Gelderland" title="Gelderland">Gelderland</a> and <a href="/wiki/Limburg_(Netherlands)" title="Limburg (Netherlands)">Limburg</a>. Limburg, in particular, differs greatly in architectural style from the rest of the Netherlands. </p>
      <p>The <a href="/wiki/Gothic_architecture" title="Gothic architecture">Gothic architecture</a> came to in the Netherlands from about 1230. Gothic buildings often had large windows, pointed arches and were richly decorated. <a href="/wiki/Brabantine_Gothic" title="Brabantine Gothic">Brabantine Gothic</a> originated with the rise of the Duchy of Brabant and spread throughout the Burgundian provinces. This architectural style is most concentrated in the province of <a href="/wiki/North-Brabant" class="mw-redirect" title="North-Brabant">North-Brabant</a>, such as <a href="/wiki/St._John%27s_Cathedral_(%27s-Hertogenbosch)" title="St. John's Cathedral ('s-Hertogenbosch)">St. John's Cathedral</a> in <a href="/wiki/%27s-Hertogenbosch" title="'s-Hertogenbosch">'s-Hertogenbosch</a>, The <a href="/wiki/Grote_kerk_(Breda)" class="mw-redirect" title="Grote kerk (Breda)">Church of Our Lady</a> in <a href="/wiki/Breda" title="Breda">Breda</a> and the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Margraves_Palace&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Margraves Palace (page does not exist)">Margraves Palace</a> in <a href="/wiki/Bergen_op_Zoom" title="Bergen op Zoom">Bergen op Zoom</a>. </p>
      <p>What many know as traditional Dutch architecture is the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Baroque_architecture" title="Dutch Baroque architecture">Dutch Baroque architecture</a> (1525 – 1630) and classicism (1630 – 1700). These style of architecture is especially in evidence in the cities of <a href="/wiki/North-Holland" class="mw-redirect" title="North-Holland">North-Holland</a>, <a href="/wiki/South-Holland" class="mw-redirect" title="South-Holland">South-Holland</a> and <a href="/wiki/Zeeland" title="Zeeland">Zeeland</a>. </p>
      <p>Other architectural styles that are common in the Netherlands are <a href="/wiki/Style_Louis_XIV" title="Style Louis XIV">Style Louis XIV</a>, <a href="/wiki/Art_Nouveau" title="Art Nouveau">Art Nouveau</a>, <a href="/wiki/Rationalism_(architecture)" title="Rationalism (architecture)">Rationalism</a>, <a href="/wiki/Neoclassicism" title="Neoclassicism">Neoclassicism</a> <a href="/wiki/Expressionist_architecture" title="Expressionist architecture">Expressionism</a>, <a href="/wiki/De_Stijl" title="De Stijl">De Stijl</a>, <a href="/wiki/Traditionalist_School_(architecture)" title="Traditionalist School (architecture)">Traditionalism</a> and <a href="/wiki/Brutalism" class="mw-redirect" title="Brutalism">Brutalism</a>. </p>
      <p>The Netherlands is the country of philosophers <a href="/wiki/Erasmus" title="Erasmus">Erasmus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Rudolf_Agricola" class="mw-redirect" title="Rudolf Agricola">Rudolf Agricola</a> and <a href="/wiki/Baruch_Spinoza" title="Baruch Spinoza">Spinoza</a>. Much of <a href="/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" title="René Descartes">Descartes</a>' major work was done in the Netherlands, where he studied at <a href="/wiki/Leiden_University" title="Leiden University">Leiden University</a> — as did geologist <a href="/wiki/James_Hutton" title="James Hutton">James Hutton</a>, British Prime Minister <a href="/wiki/John_Stuart,_3rd_Earl_of_Bute" title="John Stuart, 3rd Earl of Bute">John Stuart</a>, U.S. President <a href="/wiki/John_Quincy_Adams" title="John Quincy Adams">John Quincy Adams</a>, Physics Nobel Prize laureate <a href="/wiki/Hendrik_Lorentz" title="Hendrik Lorentz">Hendrik Lorentz</a> and <a href="/wiki/Enrico_Fermi" title="Enrico Fermi">Enrico Fermi</a>. The Dutch scientist <a href="/wiki/Christiaan_Huygens" title="Christiaan Huygens">Christiaan Huygens</a> (1629–1695) discovered <a href="/wiki/Saturn" title="Saturn">Saturn</a>'s moon <a href="/wiki/Titan_(moon)" title="Titan (moon)">Titan</a>, argued that light travelled as waves, invented the <a href="/wiki/Pendulum_clock" title="Pendulum clock">pendulum clock</a> and was the first physicist to use mathematical formulae. <a href="/wiki/Antonie_van_Leeuwenhoek" title="Antonie van Leeuwenhoek">Antonie van Leeuwenhoek</a> was the first to observe and describe <a href="/wiki/Microorganism" title="Microorganism">single-celled organisms</a> with a <a href="/wiki/Microscope" title="Microscope">microscope</a>. </p>
      <p>Replicas of Dutch buildings can be found in <a href="/wiki/Huis_Ten_Bosch_(theme_park)" title="Huis Ten Bosch (theme park)">Huis Ten Bosch</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nagasaki" title="Nagasaki">Nagasaki</a>, <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japan</a>. A similar Holland Village is being built in <a href="/wiki/Shenyang" title="Shenyang">Shenyang</a>, <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a>. <a href="/wiki/Windmill" title="Windmill">Windmills</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tulip" title="Tulip">tulips</a>, <a href="/wiki/Clog_(shoe)" class="mw-redirect" title="Clog (shoe)">wooden shoes</a>, cheese, <a href="/wiki/Delftware" title="Delftware">Delftware</a> pottery, and <a href="/wiki/Cannabis_(drug)" title="Cannabis (drug)">cannabis</a> are among the items associated with the Netherlands by tourists. </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Southern_Netherlands">Southern Netherlands</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=47" title="Edit section: Southern Netherlands">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Carnaval_2013_Netherlands.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/Carnaval_2013_Netherlands.jpg/220px-Carnaval_2013_Netherlands.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/Carnaval_2013_Netherlands.jpg/330px-Carnaval_2013_Netherlands.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/Carnaval_2013_Netherlands.jpg/440px-Carnaval_2013_Netherlands.jpg 2x" data-file-width="560" data-file-height="373"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Carnaval_2013_Netherlands.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Carnival in <a href="/wiki/North-Brabant" class="mw-redirect" title="North-Brabant">North-Brabant</a> and <a href="/wiki/Limburg_(Netherlands)" title="Limburg (Netherlands)">Limburg</a>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>In the south of the Netherlands there are some festivals that rarely or never occur in the rest of the Netherlands. These celebrations grew out of Catholic traditions, including <a href="/wiki/Carnival_in_the_Netherlands" title="Carnival in the Netherlands">Carnival</a>, lantern parades during the celebration of <a href="/wiki/Epiphany_(holiday)" title="Epiphany (holiday)">Three Kings</a>, Brabantian Day and huge <a href="/wiki/Bloemencorso" title="Bloemencorso">Bloemencorso</a>. Bloemencorso's used to occur in many places in the Netherlands, but in the 21th century, <a href="/wiki/Zundert" title="Zundert">Zundert</a> and <a href="/wiki/Valkenswaard" title="Valkenswaard">Valkenswaard</a> in <a href="/wiki/North-Brabant" class="mw-redirect" title="North-Brabant">North-Brabant</a> have taken the lead. </p>
      <p><br> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Dutch_value_system">Dutch value system</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=48" title="Edit section: Dutch value system">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/Dutch_customs_and_etiquette" title="Dutch customs and etiquette">Dutch customs and etiquette</a>
      </div> 
      <p>Dutch society is <a href="/wiki/Egalitarianism" title="Egalitarianism">egalitarian</a> and <a href="/wiki/Modernism" title="Modernism">modern</a>. The Dutch have an aversion to the non-essential.<sup id="cite_ref-Colin_White_1995_255-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Colin_White_1995-255">[242]</a></sup> Ostentatious behaviour is to be avoided. The Dutch are proud of their <a href="/wiki/Cultural_heritage" title="Cultural heritage">cultural heritage</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dutch_art" title="Dutch art">rich history in art</a> and involvement in <a href="/wiki/International_relations" title="International relations">international affairs</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Colin_White_1995_255-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Colin_White_1995-255">[242]</a></sup> </p> 
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Koningsdag_2017_Amstel.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Koningsdag_2017_Amstel.jpg/220px-Koningsdag_2017_Amstel.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="151" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Koningsdag_2017_Amstel.jpg/330px-Koningsdag_2017_Amstel.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Koningsdag_2017_Amstel.jpg/440px-Koningsdag_2017_Amstel.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3104" data-file-height="2132"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Koningsdag_2017_Amstel.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Dutch people in orange celebrating <a href="/wiki/Koningsdag" title="Koningsdag">King's Day</a> in Amsterdam, 2017
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>Dutch manners are open and direct with a no-nonsense attitude; informality combined with adherence to basic behaviour. According to a humorous source on Dutch culture, "Their directness gives many the impression that they are rude and crude — attributes they prefer to call openness."<sup id="cite_ref-Colin_White_1995_255-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Colin_White_1995-255">[242]</a></sup> A well known more serious source on Dutch etiquette is "Dealing with the Dutch" by Jacob Vossestein: "Dutch egalitarianism is the idea that people are equal, especially from a moral point of view, and accordingly, causes the somewhat ambiguous stance the Dutch have towards hierarchy and status."<sup id="cite_ref-256" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-256">[243]</a></sup> As always, manners differ between groups. Asking about basic rules will not be considered impolite. "What may strike you as being blatantly blunt topics and comments are no more embarrassing or unusual to the Dutch than discussing the weather."<sup id="cite_ref-Colin_White_1995_255-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Colin_White_1995-255">[242]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The Netherlands is one of the most secular countries of Europe, and religion is in the Netherlands generally considered as a personal matter which is not supposed to be propagated in public, although it often remains a discussion subject. For only 17% of the population religion is important and 14% goes to church weekly.<sup id="cite_ref-257" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-257">[244]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The Netherlands has a long history of social tolerance and today is regarded as a liberal country, considering <a href="/wiki/Drug_policy_of_the_Netherlands" title="Drug policy of the Netherlands">its drug policy</a> and its legalisation of <a href="/wiki/Euthanasia_in_the_Netherlands" title="Euthanasia in the Netherlands">euthanasia</a>. On 1 April 2001, the Netherlands became the first nation to legalise <a href="/wiki/Same-sex_marriage_in_the_Netherlands" title="Same-sex marriage in the Netherlands">same-sex marriage</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-258" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-258">[245]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Dutch_people_and_ecology">Dutch people and ecology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=49" title="Edit section: Dutch people and ecology">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <p>As of 2018 the Netherlands had one of the highest rates of <a href="/wiki/Carbon_dioxide" title="Carbon dioxide">carbon dioxide</a> emissions per capita in the European Union, above those of Germany, France and Belgium.<sup id="cite_ref-259" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-259">[246]</a></sup> In addition, the Dutch waste more food than any other EU citizen, at over three times the EU average <sup id="cite_ref-260" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-260">[247]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Despite this, the Netherlands has nonetheless the <a href="/wiki/Reputation" title="Reputation">reputation</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Leadership" title="Leadership">leader</a> <a href="/wiki/Country" title="Country">country</a> in <a href="/wiki/Environmental_science" title="Environmental science">environmental</a> and <a href="/wiki/Management" title="Management">population management</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-261" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-261">[248]</a></sup> In 2015, Amsterdam and Rotterdam were ranked fourth and fifth, respectively, on the <a href="/wiki/Arcadis_NV" class="mw-redirect" title="Arcadis NV">Arcadis Sustainable Cities Index</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-262" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-262">[249]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-263" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-263">[250]</a></sup> </p>
      <p><a href="/wiki/Sustainability" title="Sustainability">Sustainability</a> is a concept important for the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_people" title="Dutch people">Dutch</a>. The goal of the Dutch Government is to have a <a href="/wiki/Sustainability" title="Sustainability">sustainable</a>, reliable and affordable energy system, by 2050, in which <a href="/wiki/Carbon_dioxide_in_Earth%27s_atmosphere" title="Carbon dioxide in Earth's atmosphere"><span class="nowrap"><span class="chemf nowrap">CO<span style="display:inline-block; margin-bottom:-0.3em; vertical-align:-0.4em; line-height:1.2em; font-size:70%; text-align:left;"><br>2</span></span></span> emissions</a> have been halved and 40 percent of <a href="/wiki/Electricity" title="Electricity">electricity</a> is derived from <a href="/wiki/Sustainability" title="Sustainability">sustainable sources</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_264-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-264">[251]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The <a href="/wiki/Government" title="Government">government</a> is investing billions of euros in <a href="/wiki/Efficient_energy_use" title="Efficient energy use">energy efficiency</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sustainable_energy" title="Sustainable energy">sustainable energy</a> and <a href="/wiki/Carbon_dioxide" title="Carbon dioxide"><span class="nowrap"><span class="chemf nowrap">CO<span style="display:inline-block; margin-bottom:-0.3em; vertical-align:-0.4em; line-height:1.2em; font-size:70%; text-align:left;"><br>2</span></span></span> reduction</a>. The Kingdom also encourages Dutch <a href="/wiki/Companies" class="mw-redirect" title="Companies">companies</a> to build <a href="/wiki/Sustainable_business" title="Sustainable business">sustainable business</a>/<a href="/wiki/Project" title="Project">projects</a>/<a href="/wiki/Facility_management" title="Facility management">facilities</a>, with <a href="/wiki/Subsidy" title="Subsidy">financial aids</a> from the state to the companies or <a href="/wiki/Individual" title="Individual">individuals</a> who are active in making the <a href="/wiki/Country" title="Country">country</a> more <a href="/wiki/Sustainability" title="Sustainability">sustainable</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_264-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-264">[251]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Music">Music</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=50" title="Edit section: Music">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Music_of_the_Netherlands" title="Music of the Netherlands">Music of the Netherlands</a> and <a href="/wiki/Music_of_the_former_Netherlands_Antilles" title="Music of the former Netherlands Antilles">Music of the former Netherlands Antilles</a>
      </div> 
      <p>The Netherlands has multiple <a href="/wiki/Music" title="Music">music</a> traditions. Traditional Dutch music is a genre known as "<a href="/wiki/Levenslied" title="Levenslied">Levenslied</a>", meaning <i>Song of life</i>, to an extent comparable to a French <a href="/wiki/Chanson" title="Chanson">Chanson</a> or a German <a href="/wiki/Schlager_music" title="Schlager music">Schlager</a>. These songs typically have a simple melody and rhythm, and a straightforward structure of verses and choruses. Themes can be light, but are often sentimental and include <a href="/wiki/Love" title="Love">love</a>, <a href="/wiki/Death" title="Death">death</a> and <a href="/wiki/Loneliness" title="Loneliness">loneliness</a>. Traditional musical instruments such as the <a href="/wiki/Accordion" title="Accordion">accordion</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Barrel_organ" title="Barrel organ">barrel organ</a> are a staple of levenslied music, though in recent years many artists also use synthesisers and guitars. Artists in this genre include <a href="/wiki/Jan_Smit_(singer)" title="Jan Smit (singer)">Jan Smit</a>, <a href="/wiki/Frans_Bauer" title="Frans Bauer">Frans Bauer</a> and <a href="/wiki/Andr%C3%A9_Hazes" title="André Hazes">André Hazes</a>. </p> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:192px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Anouk,_ESC2013_press_conference_09_(crop).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Anouk%2C_ESC2013_press_conference_09_%28crop%29.jpg/190px-Anouk%2C_ESC2013_press_conference_09_%28crop%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="190" height="190" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Anouk%2C_ESC2013_press_conference_09_%28crop%29.jpg/285px-Anouk%2C_ESC2013_press_conference_09_%28crop%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Anouk%2C_ESC2013_press_conference_09_%28crop%29.jpg/380px-Anouk%2C_ESC2013_press_conference_09_%28crop%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1864" data-file-height="1864"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Anouk,_ESC2013_press_conference_09_(crop).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Pop singer <a href="/wiki/Anouk_(singer)" title="Anouk (singer)">Anouk</a> in 2013
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:192px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Coldplay_perform_%22Up%26Up%22,_Amsterdam_Arena,_June_2016_(5).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Coldplay_perform_%22Up%26Up%22%2C_Amsterdam_Arena%2C_June_2016_%285%29.jpg/190px-Coldplay_perform_%22Up%26Up%22%2C_Amsterdam_Arena%2C_June_2016_%285%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="190" height="127" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Coldplay_perform_%22Up%26Up%22%2C_Amsterdam_Arena%2C_June_2016_%285%29.jpg/285px-Coldplay_perform_%22Up%26Up%22%2C_Amsterdam_Arena%2C_June_2016_%285%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Coldplay_perform_%22Up%26Up%22%2C_Amsterdam_Arena%2C_June_2016_%285%29.jpg/380px-Coldplay_perform_%22Up%26Up%22%2C_Amsterdam_Arena%2C_June_2016_%285%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2500" data-file-height="1667"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Coldplay_perform_%22Up%26Up%22,_Amsterdam_Arena,_June_2016_(5).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div><a href="/wiki/Johan_Cruyff_Arena" title="Johan Cruyff Arena">Johan Cruyff Arena</a>, the largest Dutch concert venue
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>Contemporary Dutch <a href="/wiki/Rock_music" title="Rock music">rock</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pop_music" title="Pop music">pop music</a> (<a href="/wiki/Nederpop" title="Nederpop">Nederpop</a>) originated in the 1960s, heavily influenced by popular music from the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> and <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">Britain</a>. In the 1960s and 1970s the lyrics were mostly in English, and some tracks were instrumental. Bands such as <a href="/wiki/Shocking_Blue" title="Shocking Blue">Shocking Blue</a>, <a href="/wiki/Golden_Earring" title="Golden Earring">Golden Earring</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tee_Set" class="mw-redirect" title="Tee Set">Tee Set</a>, <a href="/wiki/George_Baker_Selection" title="George Baker Selection">George Baker Selection</a> and <a href="/wiki/Focus_(band)" title="Focus (band)">Focus</a> enjoyed international success. As of the 1980s, more and more pop musicians started working in the Dutch language, partly inspired by the huge success of the band <a href="/wiki/Doe_Maar" title="Doe Maar">Doe Maar</a>. Today Dutch rock and pop music thrives in both languages, with some artists recording in both. </p>
      <p>Current <a href="/wiki/Symphonic_metal" title="Symphonic metal">symphonic metal</a> bands <a href="/wiki/Epica_(band)" title="Epica (band)">Epica</a>, <a href="/wiki/Delain" title="Delain">Delain</a>, <a href="/wiki/ReVamp" title="ReVamp">ReVamp</a>, <a href="/wiki/The_Gathering_(band)" title="The Gathering (band)">The Gathering</a>, <a href="/wiki/Asrai" title="Asrai">Asrai</a>, <a href="/wiki/Autumn" title="Autumn">Autumn</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ayreon" title="Ayreon">Ayreon</a> and <a href="/wiki/Within_Temptation" title="Within Temptation">Within Temptation</a> as well as <a href="/wiki/Jazz" title="Jazz">jazz</a> and pop singer <a href="/wiki/Caro_Emerald" title="Caro Emerald">Caro Emerald</a> are having international success. Also, metal bands like <a href="/wiki/Hail_of_Bullets" title="Hail of Bullets">Hail of Bullets</a>, <a href="/wiki/God_Dethroned" title="God Dethroned">God Dethroned</a>, <a href="/wiki/Izegrim" title="Izegrim">Izegrim</a>, <a href="/wiki/Asphyx" title="Asphyx">Asphyx</a>, <a href="/wiki/Textures_(band)" title="Textures (band)">Textures</a>, <a href="/wiki/Present_Danger" title="Present Danger">Present Danger</a>, <a href="/wiki/Heidevolk" title="Heidevolk">Heidevolk</a> and <a href="/wiki/Slechtvalk" title="Slechtvalk">Slechtvalk</a> are popular guests at the biggest <a href="/wiki/Metal_festival" class="mw-redirect" title="Metal festival">metal festivals</a> in Europe. Contemporary local stars include pop singer <a href="/wiki/Anouk_(singer)" title="Anouk (singer)">Anouk</a>, country pop singer <a href="/wiki/Ilse_DeLange" title="Ilse DeLange">Ilse DeLange</a>, <a href="/wiki/South_Guelderish" title="South Guelderish">South Guelderish</a> and <a href="/wiki/Limburgish" title="Limburgish">Limburgish</a> dialect singing folk band <a href="/wiki/Rowwen_H%C3%A8ze" title="Rowwen Hèze">Rowwen Hèze</a>, rock band <a href="/wiki/BL%C3%98F" title="BLØF">BLØF</a> and duo <a href="/wiki/Nick_%26_Simon" title="Nick &amp; Simon">Nick &amp; Simon</a>. <a href="/wiki/Trijntje_Oosterhuis" title="Trijntje Oosterhuis">Trijntje Oosterhuis</a>, one of the country's most well known and versatile singers, has made multiple albums with famous American composers <a href="/wiki/Vince_Mendoza" title="Vince Mendoza">Vince Mendoza</a> and <a href="/wiki/Burt_Bacharach" title="Burt Bacharach">Burt Bacharach</a>. </p>
      <p>Early 1990s Dutch and <a href="/wiki/Belgium" title="Belgium">Belgian</a> <a href="/wiki/House_music" title="House music">house music</a> came together in <a href="/wiki/Eurodance" title="Eurodance">Eurodance</a> project <a href="/wiki/2_Unlimited" title="2 Unlimited">2 Unlimited</a>. Selling 18 million records,<sup id="cite_ref-265" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-265">[252]</a></sup> the two singers in the band are the most successful Dutch music artists to this day. Tracks like "<a href="/wiki/Get_Ready_for_This" title="Get Ready for This">Get Ready for This</a>" are still popular themes of U.S. sports events, like the <a href="/wiki/NHL" class="mw-redirect" title="NHL">NHL</a>. In the mid 1990s Dutch language <a href="/wiki/Hip_hop_music" title="Hip hop music">rap and hip hop</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/Dutch_hip_hop" title="Dutch hip hop">Nederhop</a></i>) also came to fruition and has become popular in the Netherlands and Belgium. Artists with North African, Caribbean or Middle Eastern origins have strongly influenced this genre. </p>
      <p>Since the 1990s, Dutch <a href="/wiki/Electronic_dance_music" title="Electronic dance music">electronic dance music</a> (EDM) gained widespread popularity in the world in many forms, from <a href="/wiki/Trance_music" title="Trance music">trance</a>, <a href="/wiki/Techno" title="Techno">techno</a> and <a href="/wiki/Gabber" title="Gabber">gabber</a> to <a href="/wiki/Hardstyle" title="Hardstyle">hardstyle</a>. Some of the world's best known dance music DJs hail from the Netherlands, including <a href="/wiki/Armin_van_Buuren" title="Armin van Buuren">Armin van Buuren</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ti%C3%ABsto" title="Tiësto">Tiësto</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hardwell" title="Hardwell">Hardwell</a>, <a href="/wiki/Martin_Garrix" title="Martin Garrix">Martin Garrix</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dash_Berlin" title="Dash Berlin">Dash Berlin</a>, <a href="/wiki/Julian_Jordan" title="Julian Jordan">Julian Jordan</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nicky_Romero" title="Nicky Romero">Nicky Romero</a>, <a href="/wiki/W%26W" title="W&amp;W">W&amp;W</a>, <a href="/wiki/Don_Diablo" title="Don Diablo">Don Diablo</a> and <a href="/wiki/Afrojack" title="Afrojack">Afrojack</a>; the first four of which have been ranked as best in the world by <a href="/wiki/DJ_Mag_Top_100_DJs" class="mw-redirect" title="DJ Mag Top 100 DJs">DJ Mag Top 100 DJs</a>. The <a href="/wiki/Amsterdam_Dance_Event" title="Amsterdam Dance Event">Amsterdam Dance Event</a> (ADE) is the world's leading electronic music conference and the biggest club festival for the many electronic subgenres on the planet.<sup id="cite_ref-266" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-266">[253]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-267" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-267">[254]</a></sup> These DJs also contribute to the world's mainstream pop music, as they frequently collaborate and produce for high-profile international artists. </p>
      <p>The Netherlands have <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_in_the_Eurovision_Song_Contest" title="Netherlands in the Eurovision Song Contest">participated</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Eurovision_Song_Contest" title="Eurovision Song Contest">Eurovision Song Contest</a> since its first edition in 1956, and have won five times. Their most recent win was in <a href="/wiki/Eurovision_Song_Contest_2019" title="Eurovision Song Contest 2019">2019</a>. </p>
      <p>In <a href="/wiki/Classical_music" title="Classical music">classical music</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jan_Sweelinck" class="mw-redirect" title="Jan Sweelinck">Jan Sweelinck</a> ranks as the Dutch most famous composer, with <a href="/wiki/Louis_Andriessen" title="Louis Andriessen">Louis Andriessen</a> amongst the best known living Dutch classical composers. <a href="/wiki/Ton_Koopman" title="Ton Koopman">Ton Koopman</a> is a Dutch conductor, organist and harpsichordist. He is also professor at the Royal Conservatory of The Hague. Notable violinists are <a href="/wiki/Janine_Jansen" title="Janine Jansen">Janine Jansen</a> and <a href="/wiki/Andr%C3%A9_Rieu" title="André Rieu">André Rieu</a>. The latter, together with his <a href="/wiki/Johann_Strauss_Orchestra" title="Johann Strauss Orchestra">Johann Strauss Orchestra</a>, has taken classical and <a href="/wiki/Waltz_(music)" title="Waltz (music)">waltz music</a> on worldwide concert tours, the size and revenue of which are otherwise only seen from the world's biggest rock and pop music acts. The most famous Dutch classical composition is "<a href="/wiki/Canto_Ostinato" title="Canto Ostinato">Canto Ostinato</a>" by <a href="/wiki/Simeon_ten_Holt" title="Simeon ten Holt">Simeon ten Holt</a>, a minimalistic composition for multiple instruments.<sup id="cite_ref-268" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-268">[255]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-269" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-269">[256]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-270" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-270">[257]</a></sup> Acclaimed harpist <a href="/wiki/Lavinia_Meijer" title="Lavinia Meijer">Lavinia Meijer</a> in 2012 released an album with works from <a href="/wiki/Philip_Glass" title="Philip Glass">Philip Glass</a> that she transcribed for harp, with approval of Glass himself.<sup id="cite_ref-271" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-271">[258]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Concertgebouw" title="Concertgebouw">Concertgebouw</a> (completed in 1888) in Amsterdam is home to the <a href="/wiki/Royal_Concertgebouw_Orchestra" title="Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra">Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra</a>, considered one of the world's finest orchestras.<sup id="cite_ref-272" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-272">[259]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Film_and_television">Film and television</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=51" title="Edit section: Film and television">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Cinema_of_the_Netherlands" title="Cinema of the Netherlands">Cinema of the Netherlands</a> and <a href="/wiki/Television_in_the_Netherlands" title="Television in the Netherlands">Television in the Netherlands</a>
      </div> 
      <p>Some Dutch films – mainly by director <a href="/wiki/Paul_Verhoeven" title="Paul Verhoeven">Paul Verhoeven</a> – have received international distribution and recognition, such as <i><a href="/wiki/Turkish_Delight_(1973_film)" title="Turkish Delight (1973 film)">Turkish Delight</a></i> ("<i>Turks Fruit</i>", 1973), <i><a href="/wiki/Soldier_of_Orange" title="Soldier of Orange">Soldier of Orange</a></i> ("<i>Soldaat van Oranje</i>", 1977), <i><a href="/wiki/Spetters" title="Spetters">Spetters</a></i> (1980) and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Fourth_Man_(1983_film)" title="The Fourth Man (1983 film)">The Fourth Man</a></i> ("<i>De Vierde Man</i>", 1983). Verhoeven then went on to direct big <a href="/wiki/Cinema_of_the_United_States" title="Cinema of the United States">Hollywood</a> movies like <i><a href="/wiki/RoboCop" title="RoboCop">RoboCop</a></i> (1987), <i><a href="/wiki/Total_Recall_(1990_film)" title="Total Recall (1990 film)">Total Recall</a></i> (1990) and <i><a href="/wiki/Basic_Instinct" title="Basic Instinct">Basic Instinct</a></i> (1992), and returned with Dutch film <i><a href="/wiki/Black_Book_(film)" title="Black Book (film)">Black Book</a></i> ("<i>Zwartboek</i>", 2006). </p>
      <p>Other well-known Dutch film directors are <a href="/wiki/Jan_de_Bont" title="Jan de Bont">Jan de Bont</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/Speed_(1994_film)" title="Speed (1994 film)">Speed</a></i>), <a href="/wiki/Anton_Corbijn" title="Anton Corbijn">Anton Corbijn</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/A_Most_Wanted_Man_(film)" title="A Most Wanted Man (film)">A Most wanted Man</a></i>), <a href="/wiki/Dick_Maas" title="Dick Maas">Dick Maas</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/De_Lift" class="mw-redirect" title="De Lift">De Lift</a></i>), <a href="/wiki/Fons_Rademakers" title="Fons Rademakers">Fons Rademakers</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/The_Assault_(film)" class="mw-redirect" title="The Assault (film)">The Assault</a></i>), and documentary makers <a href="/wiki/Bert_Haanstra" title="Bert Haanstra">Bert Haanstra</a> and <a href="/wiki/Joris_Ivens" title="Joris Ivens">Joris Ivens</a>. Film director <a href="/wiki/Theo_van_Gogh_(film_director)" title="Theo van Gogh (film director)">Theo van Gogh</a> achieved international notoriety in 2004 when he was murdered by <a href="/wiki/Mohammed_Bouyeri" title="Mohammed Bouyeri">Mohammed Bouyeri</a> in the streets of Amsterdam after directing the short film <i><a href="/wiki/Submission_(2004_film)" title="Submission (2004 film)">Submission</a></i>. </p>
      <p>Internationally, successful directors of photography from the Netherlands are <a href="/wiki/Hoyte_van_Hoytema" title="Hoyte van Hoytema">Hoyte van Hoytema</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/Interstellar_(film)" title="Interstellar (film)">Interstellar</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Spectre_(2015_film)" title="Spectre (2015 film)">Spectre</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Dunkirk_(2017_film)" title="Dunkirk (2017 film)">Dunkirk</a></i>) and <a href="/wiki/Theo_van_de_Sande" title="Theo van de Sande">Theo van de Sande</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/Wayne%27s_World" title="Wayne's World">Wayne's World</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Blade_(film)" title="Blade (film)">Blade</a></i>). Van Hoytema went to the <a href="/wiki/National_Film_School_in_%C5%81%C3%B3d%C5%BA" title="National Film School in Łódź">National Film School in Łódź</a> (<a href="/wiki/Poland" title="Poland">Poland</a>) and Van de Sande went to the <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_Film_Academy" title="Netherlands Film Academy">Netherlands Film Academy</a>. Internationally successful Dutch actors include <a href="/wiki/Famke_Janssen" title="Famke Janssen">Famke Janssen</a> (<a href="/wiki/X-Men_(film_series)" title="X-Men (film series)"><i>X-Men</i></a>), <a href="/wiki/Carice_van_Houten" title="Carice van Houten">Carice van Houten</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/Game_of_Thrones" title="Game of Thrones">Game of Thrones</a></i>), <a href="/wiki/Michiel_Huisman" title="Michiel Huisman">Michiel Huisman</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/Game_of_Thrones" title="Game of Thrones">Game of Thrones</a></i>), <a href="/wiki/Rutger_Hauer" title="Rutger Hauer">Rutger Hauer</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/Blade_Runner" title="Blade Runner">Blade Runner</a></i>), <a href="/wiki/Jeroen_Krabb%C3%A9" title="Jeroen Krabbé">Jeroen Krabbé</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/The_Living_Daylights" title="The Living Daylights">The Living Daylights</a></i>) and <a href="/wiki/Derek_de_Lint" title="Derek de Lint">Derek de Lint</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/Three_Men_and_a_Baby" title="Three Men and a Baby">Three Men and a Baby</a></i>). </p>
      <p>The Netherlands has a well developed television market, with both multiple commercial and public broadcasters. Imported TV programmes, as well as interviews with responses in a foreign language, are virtually always shown with the original sound and subtitled. Only foreign shows for children are dubbed.<sup id="cite_ref-HaGanahl2013_273-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-HaGanahl2013-273">[260]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>TV exports from the Netherlands mostly take the form of specific formats and franchises, most notably through internationally active TV production conglomerate <a href="/wiki/Endemol" title="Endemol">Endemol</a>, founded by Dutch <a href="/wiki/Mass_media" title="Mass media">media</a> <a href="/wiki/Business_magnate" title="Business magnate">tycoons</a> <a href="/wiki/John_de_Mol_Jr." title="John de Mol Jr.">John de Mol</a> and <a href="/wiki/Joop_van_den_Ende" title="Joop van den Ende">Joop van den Ende</a>. Headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Amsterdam" title="Amsterdam">Amsterdam</a>, Endemol has around 90 companies in over 30 countries. Endemol and its subsidiaries create and run reality, talent, and game show franchises worldwide, including <i><a href="/wiki/Big_Brother_(TV_series)" class="mw-redirect" title="Big Brother (TV series)">Big Brother</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Deal_or_No_Deal" title="Deal or No Deal">Deal or No Deal</a></i>. John de Mol later started his own company <a href="/wiki/Tien_(TV_channel)" title="Tien (TV channel)">Talpa</a> which created show franchises like <a href="/wiki/The_Voice_(TV_series)" class="mw-redirect" title="The Voice (TV series)"><i>The Voice</i></a> and <i><a href="/wiki/Utopia_(U.S._reality_TV_series)" class="mw-redirect" title="Utopia (U.S. reality TV series)">Utopia</a></i>. </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sports">Sports</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=52" title="Edit section: Sports">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/Sports_in_the_Netherlands" class="mw-redirect" title="Sports in the Netherlands">Sports in the Netherlands</a>
      </div> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:NED-DEN_Euro_2012_(10).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/NED-DEN_Euro_2012_%2810%29.jpg/220px-NED-DEN_Euro_2012_%2810%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="199" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/NED-DEN_Euro_2012_%2810%29.jpg/330px-NED-DEN_Euro_2012_%2810%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/NED-DEN_Euro_2012_%2810%29.jpg/440px-NED-DEN_Euro_2012_%2810%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="656" data-file-height="593"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:NED-DEN_Euro_2012_(10).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Dutch star football players <a href="/wiki/Arjen_Robben" title="Arjen Robben">Arjen Robben</a> and <a href="/wiki/Robin_van_Persie" title="Robin van Persie">Robin van Persie</a> during a game with the <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_national_football_team" title="Netherlands national football team">Netherlands</a> against <a href="/wiki/Denmark_national_football_team" title="Denmark national football team">Denmark</a> at <a href="/wiki/Euro_2012" class="mw-redirect" title="Euro 2012">Euro 2012</a>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>Approximately 4.5 million of the 16.8 million people in the Netherlands are registered to one of the 35,000 sports clubs in the country. About two-thirds of the population between 15 and 75 participates in sports weekly.<sup id="cite_ref-274" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-274">[261]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">Football</a> is the most popular participant sport in the Netherlands, before <a href="/wiki/Field_hockey" title="Field hockey">field hockey</a> and <a href="/wiki/Volleyball" title="Volleyball">volleyball</a> as the second and third most popular team sports. The <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_national_football_team" title="Netherlands national football team">Netherlands national football team</a> is one of the most popular aspects of Dutch sports; especially since the 1970s when one of the greatest footballers of all time, <a href="/wiki/Johan_Cruyff" title="Johan Cruyff">Johan Cruyff</a>, developed <a href="/wiki/Total_Football" title="Total Football">Total Football</a> with coach <a href="/wiki/Rinus_Michels" title="Rinus Michels">Rinus Michels</a>. Tennis, gymnastics and golf are the three most widely engaged in individual sports.<sup id="cite_ref-sport_275-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sport-275">[262]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Organisation of sports began at the end of the 19th century and the beginning of the 20th century. Federations for sports were established (such as the speed skating federation in 1882), rules were unified and sports clubs came into existence. A <a href="/wiki/NOC*NSF" title="NOC*NSF">Dutch National Olympic Committee</a> was established in 1912. Thus far, the nation has won 266 medals at the <a href="/wiki/Summer_Olympic_Games" title="Summer Olympic Games">Summer Olympic Games</a> and another 110 medals at the <a href="/wiki/Winter_Olympic_Games" title="Winter Olympic Games">Winter Olympic Games</a>. In international competition, Dutch national teams and athletes are dominant in several fields of sport. The <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_women%27s_national_field_hockey_team" title="Netherlands women's national field hockey team">Netherlands women's field hockey team</a> is the most successful team in <a href="/wiki/Women%27s_Hockey_World_Cup" class="mw-redirect" title="Women's Hockey World Cup">World Cup</a> history. The <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_national_baseball_team" title="Netherlands national baseball team">Netherlands baseball team</a> have won the <a href="/wiki/European_Baseball_Championship" title="European Baseball Championship">European championship</a> 20 times out of 32 events. Dutch <a href="/wiki/K-1" title="K-1">K-1</a> <a href="/wiki/Kickboxing" title="Kickboxing">kickboxers</a> have won the <a href="/wiki/K-1_World_Grand_Prix" title="K-1 World Grand Prix">K-1 World Grand Prix</a> 15 times out of 19 tournaments. The <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_women%27s_national_handball_team" title="Netherlands women's national handball team">Netherlands Women's handball team</a> holds the record of the only team in the world that consecutively reached all six semifinals of major international tournaments since 2015, winning silver and bronze at the <a href="/wiki/European_Women%27s_Handball_Championship" title="European Women's Handball Championship">European Women's Handball Championship</a> and silver, bronze and gold at the <a href="/wiki/World_Women%27s_Handball_Championship" class="mw-redirect" title="World Women's Handball Championship">World Women's Handball Championship</a>. They finished fourth at the <a href="/wiki/Handball_at_the_2016_Summer_Olympics" title="Handball at the 2016 Summer Olympics">2016 Summer Olympics</a>. </p>
      <p>The Dutch <a href="/wiki/Speed_skating" title="Speed skating">speed skaters'</a> performance at the <a href="/wiki/2014_Winter_Olympics" title="2014 Winter Olympics">2014 Winter Olympics</a>, where they won 8 out of 12 events, 23 out of 36 medals, including 4 clean sweeps, is the most dominant performance in a single sport in Olympic history. Motorcycle racing at the <a href="/wiki/TT_Circuit_Assen" title="TT Circuit Assen">TT Circuit Assen</a> has a long history. Assen is the only venue to have held a round of the Motorcycle World Championship every year since its creation in 1949. The circuit was purpose-built for the Dutch TT in 1954, with previous events having been held on public roads. </p>
      <p>The Dutch have also had success in all three of cyclings Grand Tours with <a href="/wiki/Jan_Janssen" title="Jan Janssen">Jan Janssen</a> winning the <a href="/wiki/1968_Tour_de_France" title="1968 Tour de France">1968 Tour de France</a>, more recently with <a href="/wiki/Tom_Dumoulin" title="Tom Dumoulin">Tom Dumoulin</a> winning the <a href="/wiki/2017_Giro_d%27Italia" title="2017 Giro d'Italia">2017 Giro d'Italia</a> and legendary rider <a href="/wiki/Joop_Zoetemelk" title="Joop Zoetemelk">Joop Zoetemelk</a> was the 1985 UCI World Champion, the winner of the <a href="/wiki/1979_Vuelta_a_Espana" class="mw-redirect" title="1979 Vuelta a Espana">1979 Vuelta a Espana</a>, the <a href="/wiki/1980_Tour_de_France" title="1980 Tour de France">1980 Tour de France</a> and still holds or shares numerous <a href="/wiki/Tour_de_France" title="Tour de France">Tour de France</a> records including most Tours finished and most kilometers ridden. </p>
      <p>Limburger <a href="/wiki/Max_Verstappen" title="Max Verstappen">Max Verstappen</a> currently races in <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a>, and <a href="/wiki/2016_Spanish_Grand_Prix" title="2016 Spanish Grand Prix">was the first Dutchman to win a Grand Prix</a>. The coastal resort of <a href="/wiki/Circuit_Zandvoort" title="Circuit Zandvoort">Zandvoort</a> hosted the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Grand_Prix" title="Dutch Grand Prix">Dutch Grand Prix</a> from 1958 to 1985, and has been announced to return in 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-276" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-276">[263]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_men%27s_national_volleyball_team" title="Netherlands men's national volleyball team">volleyball national men's team</a> has also been successful, winning the silver medal at the <a href="/wiki/Volleyball_at_the_1992_Summer_Olympics" title="Volleyball at the 1992 Summer Olympics">1992 Summer Olympics</a> and the gold medal <a href="/wiki/Volleyball_at_the_1996_Summer_Olympics" title="Volleyball at the 1996 Summer Olympics">four years later</a> in <a href="/wiki/Atlanta" title="Atlanta">Atlanta</a>. The biggest success of the <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_women%27s_national_volleyball_team" title="Netherlands women's national volleyball team">women's national team</a> was winning the <a href="/wiki/1995_Women%27s_European_Volleyball_Championship" title="1995 Women's European Volleyball Championship">European Championship in 1995</a> and the <a href="/wiki/2007_FIVB_Volleyball_World_Grand_Prix" title="2007 FIVB Volleyball World Grand Prix">World Grand Prix in 2007</a>. </p>
      <p>Recently <a href="/wiki/Cricket" title="Cricket">cricket</a> has made a remarkable progress in the Netherlands. Netherlands have participated in 1996, 2003, 2007 and 2011 ODI cricket World Cup. They have also qualified for 2009 and 2014 T20 World Cup. In the 2009 T20 World Cup, Netherlands defeated England, the current World Champions and inventor of the game.<sup id="cite_ref-277" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-277">[264]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Ryan_ten_Doeschate" title="Ryan ten Doeschate">Ryan ten Doeschate</a> is the only Dutch player to have played in the <a href="/wiki/Indian_Premier_League" title="Indian Premier League">IPL</a> on the team <a href="/wiki/Kolkata_Knight_Riders" title="Kolkata Knight Riders">Kolkata Knight Riders</a>. </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Cuisine">Cuisine</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=53" title="Edit section: Cuisine">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/Dutch_cuisine" title="Dutch cuisine">Dutch cuisine</a>
      </div> 
      <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r978413945/mw-parser-output/.tmulti">

          </div>

          </div>
         </div>
        </div>
        <div class="trow">
         <div class="tsingle" style="width:139px;max-width:139px">
          <div class="thumbimage" style="height:109px;overflow:hidden">

          </div>
         </div>
         <div class="tsingle" style="width:149px;max-width:149px">
          <div class="thumbimage" style="height:109px;overflow:hidden">
           <a href="/wiki/File:Oliebollen.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Oliebollen.jpg/147px-Oliebollen.jpg" decoding="async" width="147" height="110" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Oliebollen.jpg/221px-Oliebollen.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Oliebollen.jpg/294px-Oliebollen.jpg 2x" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="450"></a>

        </div>
        <div class="trow">
         <div class="tsingle" style="width:290px;max-width:290px">
          <div class="thumbimage" style="height:288px;overflow:hidden">
           <a href="/wiki/File:Bitterballen_mosterd_mayo.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Bitterballen_mosterd_mayo.jpg/288px-Bitterballen_mosterd_mayo.jpg" decoding="async" width="288" height="288" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Bitterballen_mosterd_mayo.jpg/432px-Bitterballen_mosterd_mayo.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Bitterballen_mosterd_mayo.jpg/576px-Bitterballen_mosterd_mayo.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1920" data-file-height="1920"></a>
          </div>
          <div class="thumbcaption text-align-center">
