          </div>
         </div>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>Originally, the country's cuisine was shaped by the practices of <a href="/wiki/Fishing" title="Fishing">fishing</a> and <a href="/wiki/Farming" class="mw-redirect" title="Farming">farming</a>, including the cultivation of the soil for growing crops and raising domesticated animals. Dutch cuisine is simple and straightforward, and contains many dairy products. Breakfast and lunch are typically bread with toppings, with cereal for breakfast as an alternative. Traditionally, dinner consists of potatoes, a portion of meat, and (seasonal) vegetables. The Dutch diet was relatively high in carbohydrates and fat, reflecting the dietary needs of the labourers whose culture moulded the country. Without many refinements, it is best described as rustic, though many holidays are still celebrated with special foods. In the course of the twentieth century this diet changed and became much more <a href="/wiki/Multiculturalism" title="Multiculturalism">cosmopolitan</a>, with most <a href="/wiki/Global_cuisine" title="Global cuisine">global cuisines</a> being represented in the major cities. </p>
      <p>Modern culinary writers distinguish between three general regional forms of Dutch cuisine. The regions in the northeast of the Netherlands, roughly the provinces of <a href="/wiki/Groningen_(province)" title="Groningen (province)">Groningen</a>, <a href="/wiki/Friesland" title="Friesland">Friesland</a>, <a href="/wiki/Drenthe" title="Drenthe">Drenthe</a>, <a href="/wiki/Overijssel" title="Overijssel">Overijssel</a> and <a href="/wiki/Gelderland" title="Gelderland">Gelderland</a> north of the <a href="/wiki/Grote_rivieren" title="Grote rivieren">great rivers</a> are the least populated areas of the Netherlands. The late (18th century) introduction of large scale agriculture means that the cuisine is generally known for its many kinds of meats. The relative lack of farms allowed for an abundance of <a href="/wiki/Game_(meat)" class="mw-redirect" title="Game (meat)">game</a> and <a href="/wiki/Animal_husbandry" title="Animal husbandry">husbandry</a>, though dishes near the coastal regions of Friesland, Groningen and the parts of Overijssel bordering the <a href="/wiki/IJsselmeer" title="IJsselmeer">IJsselmeer</a> also include a large amount of fish. The various dried sausages, belonging to the <a href="/wiki/Metworst" title="Metworst">metworst</a>-family of Dutch sausages are found throughout this region and are highly prized for their often very strong taste. Also smoked sausages are common, of which (<i>Gelderse</i>) <i><a href="/wiki/Rookworst" title="Rookworst">rookworst</a></i> is the most renowned. The sausage contains a lot of fat and is very juicy. Larger sausages are often eaten alongside <i><a href="/wiki/Stamppot" title="Stamppot">stamppot</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Hutspot" title="Hutspot">hutspot</a></i> or <i>zuurkool</i> (<a href="/wiki/Sauerkraut" title="Sauerkraut">sauerkraut</a>); whereas smaller ones are often eaten as a <a href="/wiki/Street_food" title="Street food">street food</a>. The provinces are also home to hard textured <a href="/wiki/Rye_bread" title="Rye bread">rye bread</a>, pastries and cookies, the latter heavily spiced with <a href="/wiki/Ginger" title="Ginger">ginger</a> or <a href="/wiki/Succade" title="Succade">succade</a> or containing small bits of meat. Various kinds of <i>Kruidkoek</i> (such as <a href="https://nl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Groninger_koek" class="extiw" title="nl:Groninger koek">Groninger koek</a>), <i><a href="https://nl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fryske_d%C3%BAmkes" class="extiw" title="nl:Fryske dúmkes">Fryske dúmkes</a></i> and <i><a href="https://nl.wikipedia.org/wiki/spekdik" class="extiw" title="nl:spekdik">spekdikken</a></i> (small savory pancakes cooked in a waffle iron) are considered typical. A notable characteristic of <i>Fries roggebrood</i> (Frisian rye bread) is its long baking time (up to 20 hours), resulting in a sweet taste and a deep dark colour.<sup id="cite_ref-278" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-278">[265]</a></sup> In terms of alcoholic beverages, the region is renowned for its many <a href="/wiki/Bitters" title="Bitters">bitters</a> (such as <i><a href="/wiki/Beerenburg" title="Beerenburg">Beerenburg</a></i>) and other high-proof liquors rather than beer, which is, apart from <i><a href="/wiki/Jenever" title="Jenever">Jenever</a></i>, typical for the rest of the country. As a coastal region, Friesland is home to low-lying grasslands, and thus has a cheese production in common with the Western cuisine. <i>Friese Nagelkaas</i> (<a href="/wiki/Friesian_Clove" title="Friesian Clove">Friesian Clove</a>) is a notable example. </p>
      <p>The provinces of <a href="/wiki/North_Holland" title="North Holland">North Holland</a>, <a href="/wiki/South_Holland" title="South Holland">South Holland</a>, <a href="/wiki/Zeeland" title="Zeeland">Zeeland</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Utrecht_(province)" title="Utrecht (province)">Utrecht</a> and the Gelderlandic area of <a href="/wiki/Betuwe" class="mw-redirect" title="Betuwe">Betuwe</a> make up the region in which western Dutch cuisine is found. Because of the abundance of water and flat grasslands that are found here, the area is known for its many dairy products, which include prominent cheeses such as <a href="/wiki/Gouda_(cheese)" class="mw-redirect" title="Gouda (cheese)">Gouda</a>, <a href="/wiki/Leyden_cheese" title="Leyden cheese">Leyden</a> (spiced cheese with cumin), and <a href="/wiki/Edam_(cheese)" class="mw-redirect" title="Edam (cheese)">Edam</a> (traditionally in small spheres) as well as <a href="/wiki/Leerdammer" title="Leerdammer">Leerdammer</a> and <a href="/wiki/Beemster_Cheese" class="mw-redirect" title="Beemster Cheese">Beemster</a>, while the adjacent <a href="/wiki/Zaanstreek" class="mw-redirect" title="Zaanstreek">Zaanstreek</a> in <a href="/wiki/North_Holland" title="North Holland">North Holland</a> has since the 16th century been known for its <a href="/wiki/Mayonnaise" title="Mayonnaise">mayonnaise</a>, typical whole-grain <a href="/wiki/Mustard_(condiment)" title="Mustard (condiment)">mustards</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-279" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-279">[266]</a></sup> and <a href="/wiki/Chocolate" title="Chocolate">chocolate</a> industry. Zeeland and South Holland produce a lot of butter, which contains a larger amount of <a href="/wiki/Milkfat" class="mw-redirect" title="Milkfat">milkfat</a> than most other European butter varieties. A by-product of the butter-making process, <i>karnemelk</i> (<a href="/wiki/Buttermilk" title="Buttermilk">buttermilk</a>), is also considered typical for this region. <a href="/wiki/Seafood" title="Seafood">Seafood</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Soused_herring" title="Soused herring">soused herring</a>, <a href="/wiki/Blue_mussel" title="Blue mussel">mussels</a> (called <i>Zeeuwse Mossels</i>, since all Dutch mussels for consumption are cleaned in Zeeland's <a href="/wiki/Oosterschelde" class="mw-redirect" title="Oosterschelde">Oosterschelde</a>), <a href="/wiki/European_eel" title="European eel">eels</a>, <a href="/wiki/Oyster" title="Oyster">oysters</a> and <a href="/wiki/Shrimp" title="Shrimp">shrimps</a> are widely available and typical for the region. <i><a href="https://nl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kibbeling" class="extiw" title="nl:Kibbeling">Kibbeling</a></i>, once a local delicacy consisting of small chunks of battered <a href="/wiki/Whitefish_(fisheries_term)" title="Whitefish (fisheries term)">white fish</a>, has become a national <a href="/wiki/Fast_food" title="Fast food">fast food</a>, just as <a href="https://nl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lekkerbekje" class="extiw" title="nl:Lekkerbekje">lekkerbek</a>. Pastries in this area tend to be quite doughy, and often contain large amounts of sugar; either caramelised, powdered or crystallised. The <i><a href="/wiki/Oliebol" title="Oliebol">oliebol</a></i> (in its modern form) and <i><a href="/wiki/Zeeuwse_bolus" title="Zeeuwse bolus">Zeeuwse bolus</a></i> are good examples. Cookies are also produced in great number and tend to contain a lot of butter and sugar, like <i><a href="/wiki/Stroopwafel" title="Stroopwafel">stroopwafel</a></i>, as well as a filling of some kind, mostly almond, like <i><a href="https://nl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gevulde_koek" class="extiw" title="nl:Gevulde koek">gevulde koek</a></i>. The traditional alcoholic beverages of this region are <a href="/wiki/Beer" title="Beer">beer</a> (strong pale lager) and <i><a href="/wiki/Jenever" title="Jenever">Jenever</a></i>, a high proof <a href="/wiki/Juniper" title="Juniper">juniper</a>-flavored spirit, that came to be known in England as <a href="/wiki/Gin" title="Gin">gin</a>. A noted exception within the traditional Dutch alcoholic landscape, <i><a href="/wiki/Advocaat" title="Advocaat">Advocaat</a></i>, a rich and creamy liqueur made from eggs, sugar and brandy, is also native to this region. </p>
      <p>The Southern Dutch cuisine consists of the cuisines of the Dutch provinces of <a href="/wiki/North_Brabant" title="North Brabant">North Brabant</a> and <a href="/wiki/Limburg_(Netherlands)" title="Limburg (Netherlands)">Limburg</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Flemish_Region" title="Flemish Region">Flemish Region</a> in <a href="/wiki/Belgium" title="Belgium">Belgium</a>. It is renowned for its many rich pastries, soups, stews and vegetable dishes and is often called Burgundian which is a Dutch idiom invoking the rich Burgundian court which ruled the Low Countries in the Middle Ages, renowned for its splendor and great feasts. It is the only Dutch culinary region that developed an <a href="/wiki/Haute_cuisine" title="Haute cuisine">haute cuisine</a>. Pastries are abundant, often with rich fillings of cream, custard or fruits. Cakes, such as the <i><a href="/wiki/Vlaai" title="Vlaai">Vlaai</a></i> from Limburg and the <i>Moorkop</i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Bossche_Bol" class="mw-redirect" title="Bossche Bol">Bossche Bol</a></i> from Brabant, are typical pastries. Savoury pastries also occur, with the <i lang="nl" title="Dutch-language text">worstenbroodje</i> (a roll with a sausage of <a href="/wiki/Ground_beef" title="Ground beef">ground beef</a>, literally translates into sausage bread) being the most popular. The traditional alcoholic beverage of the region is beer. There are many local brands, ranging from <i><a href="/wiki/Trappist_beer" title="Trappist beer">Trappist</a></i> to <i><a href="/wiki/Kriek_lambic" title="Kriek lambic">Kriek</a></i>. 5 of the 10 <i>International Trappist Association</i> recognised breweries in the world, are located in the Southern Dutch cultural area. Beer, like wine in French cuisine, is also used in cooking; often in stews. </p>
      <p>In early 2014, <a href="/wiki/Oxfam" title="Oxfam">Oxfam</a> ranked the Netherlands as the country with the most nutritious, plentiful and healthy food, in a comparison of 125 countries.<sup id="cite_ref-280" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-280">[267]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-281" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-281">[268]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Colonial_heritage">Colonial heritage</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=54" title="Edit section: Colonial heritage">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Empire" title="Dutch Empire">Dutch Empire</a>
      </div> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Further information: <a href="/wiki/Dutch_East_Indies" title="Dutch East Indies">Dutch East Indies</a> and <a href="/wiki/Indos_in_the_Dutch_East_Indies" class="mw-redirect" title="Indos in the Dutch East Indies">Indos in the Dutch East Indies</a>
      </div> 
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:GezichtOpNieuwAmsterdam.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/GezichtOpNieuwAmsterdam.jpg/200px-GezichtOpNieuwAmsterdam.jpg" decoding="async" width="200" height="136" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/GezichtOpNieuwAmsterdam.jpg/300px-GezichtOpNieuwAmsterdam.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/GezichtOpNieuwAmsterdam.jpg/400px-GezichtOpNieuwAmsterdam.jpg 2x" data-file-width="7276" data-file-height="4964"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:GezichtOpNieuwAmsterdam.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div><a href="/wiki/New_Amsterdam" title="New Amsterdam">New Amsterdam</a> as it appeared in 1664. Under British rule it became known as <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York</a>.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>From the exploitations in the <a href="/wiki/Mughal_Empire" title="Mughal Empire">Mughal Empire</a> in the 17th century, to the <a href="/wiki/New_Imperialism" title="New Imperialism">colonisations</a> in the 19th century, <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Empire" title="Dutch Empire">Dutch imperial possessions</a> continued to expand, reaching their greatest extent by establishing a hegemony of the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_East_Indies" title="Dutch East Indies">Dutch East Indies</a> in the early 20th century. The Dutch East Indies, which later formed modern-day Indonesia, was one of the most valuable European colonies in the world and the most important one for the Netherlands.<sup id="cite_ref-282" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-282">[269]</a></sup> Over 350 years of mutual heritage has left a significant cultural mark on the Netherlands. </p>
      <p>In the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Golden_Age" title="Dutch Golden Age">Dutch Golden Age</a> of the 17th century, the Netherlands urbanised considerably, mostly financed by corporate revenue from the Asian trade monopolies. Social status was based on merchants' income, which reduced <a href="/wiki/Feudalism" title="Feudalism">feudalism</a> and considerably changed the dynamics of Dutch society. When the <a href="/wiki/Monarchy_of_the_Netherlands" title="Monarchy of the Netherlands">Dutch royal family</a> was established in 1815, much of its wealth came from Colonial trade.<sup id="cite_ref-283" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-283">[270]</a></sup> </p> 
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:De_Lannoy_Surrender.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/De_Lannoy_Surrender.JPG/200px-De_Lannoy_Surrender.JPG" decoding="async" width="200" height="150" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/De_Lannoy_Surrender.JPG/300px-De_Lannoy_Surrender.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/De_Lannoy_Surrender.JPG/400px-De_Lannoy_Surrender.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2816" data-file-height="2112"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:De_Lannoy_Surrender.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div><a href="/wiki/Eustachius_De_Lannoy" title="Eustachius De Lannoy">Eustachius De Lannoy</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_East_India_Company" title="Dutch East India Company">Dutch East India Company</a> surrenders to Maharaja <a href="/wiki/Marthanda_Varma" title="Marthanda Varma">Marthanda Varma</a> of the <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indian</a> <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_Travancore" class="mw-redirect" title="Kingdom of Travancore">Kingdom of Travancore</a> after the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Colachel" title="Battle of Colachel">Battle of Colachel</a>. (Depiction at <a href="/wiki/Padmanabhapuram_Palace" title="Padmanabhapuram Palace">Padmanabhapuram Palace</a>)
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>By the 17th century, the Dutch East India Company established their base in parts of <a href="/wiki/Ceylon" class="mw-redirect" title="Ceylon">Ceylon</a> (modern-day <a href="/wiki/Sri_Lanka" title="Sri Lanka">Sri Lanka</a>). Afterward, they established ports in <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Malabar" title="Dutch Malabar">Dutch occupied Malabar</a>, leading to <a href="/wiki/Dutch_India" title="Dutch India">Dutch settlements and trading posts in India</a>. However, their expansion into <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a> was halted, after their defeat in the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Colachel" title="Battle of Colachel">Battle of Colachel</a> by the <a href="/wiki/Travancore" title="Travancore">Kingdom of Travancore</a>, during the <a href="/wiki/Travancore-Dutch_War" class="mw-redirect" title="Travancore-Dutch War">Travancore-Dutch War</a>. The Dutch never recovered from the defeat and no longer posed a large colonial threat to <a href="/wiki/Bengal_Subah" title="Bengal Subah">Bengal Subah</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-284" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-284">[271]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-285" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-285">[272]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Universities such as the <a href="/wiki/Leiden_University" title="Leiden University">Leiden University</a>, founded in the 16th century, have developed into leading knowledge centres for <a href="/wiki/Southeast_Asia" title="Southeast Asia">Southeast Asian</a> and Indonesian studies.<sup id="cite_ref-286" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-286">[n]</a></sup> Leiden University has produced leading academics such as <a href="/wiki/Christiaan_Snouck_Hurgronje" title="Christiaan Snouck Hurgronje">Christiaan Snouck Hurgronje</a>, and still has academics who specialise in Indonesian languages and cultures. Leiden University and in particular <a href="/wiki/KITLV" class="mw-redirect" title="KITLV">KITLV</a> are educational and scientific institutions that to this day share both an intellectual and historical interest in Indonesian studies. Other scientific institutions in the Netherlands include the Amsterdam <a href="/wiki/Tropenmuseum" title="Tropenmuseum">Tropenmuseum</a>, an anthropological museum with massive collections of Indonesian art, culture, ethnography and anthropology. </p> 
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:COLLECTIE_TROPENMUSEUM_Een_Europeaan_vaccineert_Indonesische_pati%C3%ABnten_met_neosalvarsaan_tegen_de_ziekte_framboesia_TMnr_10006691.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b2/COLLECTIE_TROPENMUSEUM_Een_Europeaan_vaccineert_Indonesische_pati%C3%ABnten_met_neosalvarsaan_tegen_de_ziekte_framboesia_TMnr_10006691.jpg/200px-COLLECTIE_TROPENMUSEUM_Een_Europeaan_vaccineert_Indonesische_pati%C3%ABnten_met_neosalvarsaan_tegen_de_ziekte_framboesia_TMnr_10006691.jpg" decoding="async" width="200" height="219" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b2/COLLECTIE_TROPENMUSEUM_Een_Europeaan_vaccineert_Indonesische_pati%C3%ABnten_met_neosalvarsaan_tegen_de_ziekte_framboesia_TMnr_10006691.jpg/300px-COLLECTIE_TROPENMUSEUM_Een_Europeaan_vaccineert_Indonesische_pati%C3%ABnten_met_neosalvarsaan_tegen_de_ziekte_framboesia_TMnr_10006691.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b2/COLLECTIE_TROPENMUSEUM_Een_Europeaan_vaccineert_Indonesische_pati%C3%ABnten_met_neosalvarsaan_tegen_de_ziekte_framboesia_TMnr_10006691.jpg/400px-COLLECTIE_TROPENMUSEUM_Een_Europeaan_vaccineert_Indonesische_pati%C3%ABnten_met_neosalvarsaan_tegen_de_ziekte_framboesia_TMnr_10006691.jpg 2x" data-file-width="638" data-file-height="700"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:COLLECTIE_TROPENMUSEUM_Een_Europeaan_vaccineert_Indonesische_pati%C3%ABnten_met_neosalvarsaan_tegen_de_ziekte_framboesia_TMnr_10006691.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>A Dutch doctor vaccinating <a href="/wiki/Native_Indonesians" title="Native Indonesians">Indonesian</a> patients
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The traditions of the <a href="/wiki/Royal_Dutch_East_Indies_Army" class="mw-redirect" title="Royal Dutch East Indies Army">Royal Dutch East Indies Army</a> (KNIL) are maintained by the <a href="/wiki/Regiment_Van_Heutsz" class="mw-redirect" title="Regiment Van Heutsz">Regiment Van Heutsz</a> of the modern <a href="/wiki/Royal_Netherlands_Army" title="Royal Netherlands Army">Royal Netherlands Army</a>. A dedicated <i><a href="/wiki/Bronbeek" title="Bronbeek">Bronbeek</a> Museum</i>, a former home for retired KNIL soldiers, exists in <a href="/wiki/Arnhem" title="Arnhem">Arnhem</a> to this day. </p>
      <p>A specific segment of Dutch literature called <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Indies_literature" title="Dutch Indies literature">Dutch Indies literature</a> still exists and includes established authors, such as <a href="/wiki/Louis_Couperus" title="Louis Couperus">Louis Couperus</a>, the writer of "The Hidden Force", taking the colonial era as an important source of inspiration.<sup id="cite_ref-287" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-287">[273]</a></sup> One of the great masterpieces of <a href="/wiki/Dutch_literature" class="mw-redirect" title="Dutch literature">Dutch literature</a> is the book "<a href="/wiki/Max_Havelaar" title="Max Havelaar">Max Havelaar</a>", written by <a href="/wiki/Multatuli" title="Multatuli">Multatuli</a> in 1860.<sup id="cite_ref-288" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-288">[274]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The majority of Dutchmen that repatriated to the Netherlands after and during the Indonesian revolution are <a href="/wiki/Indo_people" title="Indo people">Indo</a> (Eurasian), native to the islands of the Dutch East Indies. This relatively large Eurasian population had developed over a period of 400 years and were classified by colonial law as belonging to the European legal community.<sup id="cite_ref-289" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-289">[275]</a></sup> In Dutch they are referred to as <i>Indische Nederlanders</i> or as Indo (short for Indo-European).<sup id="cite_ref-290" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-290">[276]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Including their second generation descendants, Indos are currently the largest foreign-born group in the Netherlands. In 2008, the Dutch Central Bureau for Statistics (CBS)<sup id="cite_ref-291" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-291">[277]</a></sup> registered 387,000 first- and second-generation Indos living in the Netherlands.<sup id="cite_ref-292" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-292">[278]</a></sup> Although considered fully assimilated into Dutch society, as the main ethnic minority in the Netherlands, these 'repatriants' have played a pivotal role in introducing elements of Indonesian culture into Dutch mainstream culture. </p>
      <p>Many Indonesian dishes and foodstuffs have become commonplace in the Netherlands. <a href="/wiki/Rijsttafel" title="Rijsttafel">Rijsttafel</a>, a colonial culinary concept, and dishes such as <a href="/wiki/Nasi_goreng" title="Nasi goreng">Nasi goreng</a> and <a href="/wiki/Satay" title="Satay">satay</a> are very popular in the country.<sup id="cite_ref-293" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-293">[279]</a></sup> Practically any town of any size in the Netherlands has a "toko" (a Dutch Indonesian Shop) or a Chinese-Indonesian restaurant,<sup id="cite_ref-294" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-294">[280]</a></sup> and many '<a href="/wiki/Pasar_Malam" class="mw-redirect" title="Pasar Malam">Pasar Malam</a>' (Night market in Malay/Indonesian) fairs are organised throughout the year. </p> 
      <div style="clear:both;"></div> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=55" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r936637989">.mw-parser-output .portal{border:solid #aaa 1px;padding:0}.mw-parser-output .portal.tleft{margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0}.mw-parser-output .portal.tright{margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 1em}.mw-parser-output .portal>ul{display:table;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0.1em;max-width:175px;background:#f9f9f9;font-size:85%;line-height:110%;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold}.mw-parser-output .portal>ul>li{display:table-row}.mw-parser-output .portal>ul>li>span:first-child{display:table-cell;padding:0.2em;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center}.mw-parser-output .portal>ul>li>span:last-child{display:table-cell;padding:0.2em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em;vertical-align:middle}</style>
      <div role="navigation" aria-label="Portals" class="noprint portal plainlist tright"> 
       <ul> 
        <li><span><img alt="flag" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/20/Flag_of_the_Netherlands.svg/32px-Flag_of_the_Netherlands.svg.png" decoding="async" width="32" height="21" class="noviewer thumbborder" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/20/Flag_of_the_Netherlands.svg/48px-Flag_of_the_Netherlands.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/20/Flag_of_the_Netherlands.svg/64px-Flag_of_the_Netherlands.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="900" data-file-height="600"></span><span><a href="/wiki/Portal:Netherlands" title="Portal:Netherlands">Netherlands portal</a></span></li>
       </ul>
      </div> 
      <ul>
       <li><a href="/wiki/Outline_of_the_Netherlands" title="Outline of the Netherlands">Outline of the Netherlands</a></li>
      </ul> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=56" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;"> 
       <div class="mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns">
        <ol class="references"> 
         <li id="cite_note-central_cities-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-central_cities_1-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-central_cities_1-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Amsterdam is the constitutional capital, while the government and the royal family are seated in The Hague.</span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-co-official_languages-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-co-official_languages_3-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Apart from Dutch, English is an official language in the special municipalities of <a href="/wiki/Saba" title="Saba">Saba</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sint_Eustatius" title="Sint Eustatius">Sint Eustatius</a>, Papiamentu is an official language in the special municipality of <a href="/wiki/Bonaire" title="Bonaire">Bonaire</a>, and Frisian is an official language in the province of <a href="/wiki/Friesland" title="Friesland">Friesland</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-official-and-recognised-languages_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-official-and-recognised-languages-2">[1]</a></sup></span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-recognised_languages-4"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-recognised_languages_4-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Having ratified the <a href="/wiki/European_Charter_for_Regional_or_Minority_Languages" title="European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages">European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages</a> in 1996, the Dutch government recognises Dutch Low Saxon, Limburgish, Sinte Romani and Yiddish as regional or non-territorial minority languages.<sup id="cite_ref-official-and-recognised-languages_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-official-and-recognised-languages-2">[1]</a></sup></span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-15"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The euro is used in the European part of the Netherlands and replaced the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_guilder" title="Dutch guilder">Dutch guilder</a> in 2002. The United States dollar is used in the <a href="/wiki/Caribbean_Netherlands" title="Caribbean Netherlands">Caribbean Netherlands</a> and replaced the <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_Antillean_guilder" title="Netherlands Antillean guilder">Netherlands Antillean guilder</a> in 2011.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[11]</a></sup></span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-16"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">CET and CEST are used in the European Netherlands, and AST is used in the Caribbean Netherlands.</span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-18"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-18">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">+599 was the country code designated for the now dissolved <a href="/wiki/Netherlands_Antilles" title="Netherlands Antilles">Netherlands Antilles</a>. The Caribbean Netherlands still use +599&nbsp;7 (for Bonaire), +599&nbsp;3 (for Sint Eustatius), and +599&nbsp;4 (for Saba).</span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-19"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-19">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">.nl is the common internet top level domain name for the Netherlands. The <a href="/wiki/.eu" title=".eu">.eu</a> domain is also used, as it is shared with other <a href="/wiki/European_Union" title="European Union">European Union</a> member states. .bq is designated, but not in use, for the <a href="/wiki/Caribbean_Netherlands" title="Caribbean Netherlands">Caribbean Netherlands</a>.</span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-24"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-24">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">In the <a href="/wiki/Caribbean_Sea" title="Caribbean Sea">Caribbean Sea</a>, the country has maritime borders with <a href="/wiki/Anguilla" title="Anguilla">Anguilla</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cura%C3%A7ao" title="Curaçao">Curaçao</a>, <a href="/wiki/France" title="France">France</a> (<a href="/wiki/Collectivity_of_Saint_Martin" title="Collectivity of Saint Martin">Saint Martin</a> and <a href="/wiki/Saint_Barth%C3%A9lemy" title="Saint Barthélemy">Saint Barthélemy</a>), <a href="/wiki/Saint_Kitts_and_Nevis" title="Saint Kitts and Nevis">Saint Kitts and Nevis</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sint_Maarten" title="Sint Maarten">Sint Maarten</a>, the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Virgin_Islands" title="United States Virgin Islands">U.S. Virgin Islands</a> and <a href="/wiki/Venezuela" title="Venezuela">Venezuela</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Caribbean-Borders_23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Caribbean-Borders-23">[16]</a></sup></span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-40"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-40">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Up one place from previous rankings.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">[31]</a></sup></span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-215"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-215">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Provided statistics show Protestants by their allegiance to congregations of two denominations that do not exist anymore. In 2004, the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Reformed_Church" title="Dutch Reformed Church">Dutch Reformed Church</a> (NHK), the <a href="/wiki/Reformed_Churches_in_the_Netherlands" title="Reformed Churches in the Netherlands">Reformed Churches in the Netherlands</a> (GKN) and the <a href="/wiki/Evangelical_Lutheran_Church_in_the_Kingdom_of_the_Netherlands" title="Evangelical Lutheran Church in the Kingdom of the Netherlands">Evangelical Lutheran Church in the Kingdom of the Netherlands</a> merged to form the <a href="/wiki/Protestant_Church_in_the_Netherlands" title="Protestant Church in the Netherlands">Protestant Church in the Netherlands</a> (PKN) and officially no longer exist. However, many people still tend to give their older affiliation even after the merger. People who declared themselves simply as belonging to the <a href="/wiki/Protestant_Church_in_the_Netherlands" title="Protestant Church in the Netherlands">Protestant Church in the Netherlands</a> did not give an information about belonging to an older affiliation. For example, <a href="/wiki/Lutherans" class="mw-redirect" title="Lutherans">Members</a> of the former <a href="/wiki/Evangelical_Lutheran_Church_in_the_Kingdom_of_the_Netherlands" title="Evangelical Lutheran Church in the Kingdom of the Netherlands">Evangelical Lutheran Church in the Kingdom of the Netherlands</a> happened to do so. People who identified with one of those three categories (NHK/GKN/or simply PKN) are all members of the Protestant Church in the Netherlands.<sup id="cite_ref-214" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-214">[205]</a></sup></span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-216"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-216">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Including other Protestants that are not members of the <a href="/wiki/Protestant_Church_in_the_Netherlands" title="Protestant Church in the Netherlands">Protestant Church in the Netherlands</a>.</span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-241"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-241">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Only 11 stations are served less than twice an hour during weekdays.</span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-250"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-250">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Up from 31% vs. 19% naming the bike their main mode of transport for daily activities in 2011.<sup id="cite_ref-248" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-248">[236]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-249" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-249">[237]</a></sup></span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-286"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-286">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Some of the university faculties still include: Indonesian Languages and Cultures; South-east Asia and Oceania Languages and Cultures; Cultural Anthropology.</span> </li> 
        </ol>
       </div>
      </div>

           <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r999302996"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2019/01/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=90&amp;pr.y=17&amp;sy=2019&amp;ey=2019&amp;scsm=1&amp;ssd=1&amp;sort=country&amp;ds=.&amp;br=1&amp;c=138&amp;s=NGDPD%2CPPPGDP%2CNGDPDPC%2CPPPPC&amp;grp=0&amp;a=">"Netherlands"</a>.          <li id="cite_note-eurogini-12"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-eurogini_12-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">
           <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r999302996"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/tgm/table.do?tab=table&amp;init=1&amp;language=en&amp;pcode=tessi190&amp;plugin=1">"Gini coefficient of equivalised disposable income – EU-SILC survey"</a>. <i>ec.europa.eu/eurostat</i>. <a href="/wiki/Eurostat" title="Eurostat">Eurostat</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. In: Kontinuität und Diskontinuität: Germania inferior am Beginn und am Ende der römischen Herrschaft; Beiträge des deutsch-niederländischen Kolloquiums in der Katholieke Universiteit Nijmegen, (27. bis 30.6.2001)</i></a>. Walter de Gruyter. pp.&nbsp;53–83. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&nbsp;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9783110176889" title="Special:BookSources/9783110176889"><bdi>9783110176889</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Why+did+they+leave%3F+Why+did+they+stay%3F+On+continuity+versus+discontinuity+from+Roman+times+to+Early+Middle+Ages+in+the+western+coastal+area+of+the+Netherlands.+In%3A+Kontinuit%C3%A4t+und+Diskontinuit%C3%A4t%3A+Germania+inferior+am+Beginn+und+am+Ende+der+r%C3%B6mischen+Herrschaft%3B+Beitr%C3%A4ge+des+deutsch-niederl%C3%A4ndischen+Kolloquiums+in+der+Katholieke+Universiteit+Nijmegen%2C+%2827.+bis+30.6.2001%29&amp;rft.pages=53-83&amp;rft.pub=Walter+de+Gruyter&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.isbn=9783110176889&amp;rft.aulast=De+Koning&amp;rft.aufirst=Jan&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DrCJOxv2JiVQC%26pg%3DPA53&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANetherlands" class="Z3988"></span></span> </li>

         <li id="cite_note-79"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-79">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">
           <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r999302996"><cite id="CITEREFMotley1859" class="citation book cs1">Motley, John (1859). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/risedutchrepubl01motlgoog"><i>The Rise of the Dutch Republic, Volume 2</i></a>. pp.&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/risedutchrepubl01motlgoog/page/n33">25</a>. <q>On more than one occasion men were seen hanging their own brothers, who had been taken prisoners in the enemy's ranks.... A Spaniard had ceased to be human in their eyes. On one occasion, a surgeon at Veer cut the heart from a Spanish prisoner, nailed it on a vessel's prow, and invited the townsmen to come and fasten their teeth in it, which many did with savage satisfaction.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Rise+of+the+Dutch+Republic%2C+Volume+2&amp;rft.pages=25&amp;rft.date=1859&amp;rft.aulast=Motley&amp;rft.aufirst=John&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Frisedutchrepubl01motlgoog&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANetherlands" class="Z3988"></span></span> </li>

Eerste kamer der Staten-Generaal<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">15 October</span> 2010</span>. <q>De openbare lichamen vallen rechtstreeks onder het Rijk omdat zij geen deel uitmaken van een provincie. <br>"Through the establishment of the BES islands as public bodies, rather than communities, the BES islands' rules may deviate from the rules in the European part of the Netherlands. The Dutch legislation will be introduced gradually. The public bodies fall directly under the central government because they are not part of a province."</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=31.954%2C+Wet+openbare+lichamen+Bonaire%2C+Sint+Eustatius+en+Saba&amp;rft.pub=Eerste+kamer+der+Staten-Generaal&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.eerstekamer.nl%2Fwetsvoorstel%2F31954_wet_openbare_lichamen&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANetherlands" class="Z3988"></span></span> </li>

Retrieved <span class="nowrap">21 August</span> 2012</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Empires+and+Colonies&amp;rft.pages=201-&amp;rft.pub=Polity&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7456-2614-7&amp;rft.au=Hart%2C+Jonathan&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DLnevC1FYdnEC%26pg%3DPA201&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANetherlands" class="Z3988"></span></span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-283"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-283">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">To this day the Dutch Royal family is in fact the wealthiest family of the Netherlands. One of the foundations of its wealth was the colonial trade.
           <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r999302996"><cite id="CITEREFPendletonSerafin2007" class="citation news cs1">Pendleton, Devon; Serafin, Tatiana (30 August 2007). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.forbes.com/2007/08/30/worlds-richest-royals-biz-royals07-cx_lk_0830royalintro_slide_15.html?thisSpeed=30000">"In Pictures: The World's Richest Royals"</a>. <i>Forbes</i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">5 March</span> 2010</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Forbes&amp;rft.atitle=In+Pictures%3A+The+World%27s+Richest+Royals&amp;rft.date=2007-08-30&amp;rft.aulast=Pendleton&amp;rft.aufirst=Devon&amp;rft.au=Serafin%2C+Tatiana&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.forbes.com%2F2007%2F08%2F30%2Fworlds-richest-royals-biz-royals07-cx_lk_0830royalintro_slide_15.html%3FthisSpeed%3D30000&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANetherlands" class="Z3988"></span></span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-284"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-284">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">
           <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r999302996"><cite id="CITEREFKoshy1989" class="citation book cs1">Koshy, M. O. (1989). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=ro8SLhyAc9AC"><i>The Dutch Power in Kerala, 1729–1758</i></a>. Mittal Publications. p.&nbsp;61. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&nbsp;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-81-7099-136-6" title="Special:BookSources/978-81-7099-136-6"><bdi>978-81-7099-136-6</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Dutch+Power+in+Kerala%2C+1729%E2%80%931758&amp;rft.pages=61&amp;rft.pub=Mittal+Publications&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.isbn=978-81-7099-136-6&amp;rft.aulast=Koshy&amp;rft.aufirst=M.+O.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dro8SLhyAc9AC&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANetherlands" class="Z3988"></span></span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-285"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-285">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="http://mod.nic.in/samachar/april15-04/body.html#l1">[1]</a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160312081154/http://mod.nic.in/samachar/april15-04/body.html">Archived</a> 12 March 2016 at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a> 9th Madras Regiment</span> </li> 
         <li id="cite_note-287"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-287">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Nieuwenhuys, Rob <i>Mirror of the Indies: A History of Dutch Colonial Literature</i> translated from Dutch by E. M. Beekman (Publisher: Periplus, 1999) <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://dannyreviews.com/h/Mirror_Indies.html">Book review.</a></span> </li>

           <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r999302996"><a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&nbsp;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9971-69-373-9" title="Special:BookSources/9971-69-373-9">9971-69-373-9</a></span> </li>

      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Further_reading">Further reading</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Netherlands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=58" title="Edit section: Further reading">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <dl>
       <dt>
        Geography and environment
       </dt>
      </dl> 
      <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1004355016">.mw-parser-output .refbegin{font-size:90%;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>ul{margin-left:0}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>ul>li{margin-left:0;padding-left:3.2em;text-indent:-3.2em}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents ul,.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents ul li{list-style:none}@media(max-width:720px){.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>ul>li{padding-left:1.6em;text-indent:-1.6em}}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-100{font-size:100%}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-columns{margin-top:0.3em}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-columns dl,.mw-parser-output .refbegin-columns ol,.mw-parser-output .refbegin-columns ul{margin-top:0}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-columns li,.mw-parser-output .refbegin-columns dd{page-break-inside:avoid;break-inside:avoid-column}</style>
      <div class="refbegin" style="">

        <li>Burke, Gerald L. <i>The making of Dutch towns: A study in urban development from the 10th–17th centuries</i> (1960)</li>

        <li>Meijer, Henk. <i>Compact geography of the Netherlands</i> (1985)</li> 
        <li>Riley, R. C., and G. J. Ashworth. <i>Benelux: An Economic Geography of Belgium, the Netherlands, and Luxembourg</i> (1975) <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.questia.com/read/85882918/benelux-an-economic-geography-of-belgium-the-netherlands">online</a></li>

      <div class="refbegin" style=""> 
       <ul>
        <li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20180824080557/https://www.hollandtradeandinvest.com/binaries/hollandtrade/documents/publications/holland-compared-2017/06/30/holland-compared-2nd-edition-2016/1392_CU+Holland+Compared+2nd+2017+III.pdf">Holland Compared 2nd edition 2017</a> – 95 page booklet by Holland's commercial website, with facts and figures about the Netherlands, comparing the country's economic indicators with those of other countries.</li>

                   <li><a href="/wiki/Abkhazia" title="Abkhazia">Abkhazia</a></li>

                  </ul> 
                 </div></td>
               </tr>

                  <div class="plainlist">
                   <ul>
                    <li><sup>1</sup> <a href="/wiki/Island#Oceanic_islands" title="Island">Oceanic islands</a> within the vicinity of Europe are usually grouped with the continent even though they are not situated on its continental shelf.</li>
                    <li><sup>2</sup> Some countries completely outside the conventional geographical boundaries of Europe are commonly associated with the continent due to ethnological links.</li>
                   </ul>

                <th scope="row" class="navbox-group" style="width:1%">Agreements</th>
                <td class="navbox-list navbox-odd" style="text-align:left;border-left-width:2px;border-left-style:solid;width:100%;padding:0px">

                   <li><a href="/wiki/Agreement_on_Agriculture" title="Agreement on Agriculture">Agriculture</a></li>

                   <li><a href="/wiki/Special_administrative_regions_of_China" title="Special administrative regions of China">Special administrative regions of the People's Republic of China</a>, participates as "Hong Kong, China" and "Macao China".</li> 
                   <li>Officially the Republic of China, participates as "<a href="/wiki/Chinese_Taipei" title="Chinese Taipei">Separate Customs Territory of Taiwan, Penghu, Kinmen and Matsu</a>", and "Chinese Taipei" in short.</li>
                  </ol> 
                 </div></td>
               </tr>
              </tbody>
             </table>
            </div>

                           <li><a href="/wiki/Arguin" title="Arguin">Arguin</a></li>

                          </ul> 
                         </div></td>
                       </tr>
